WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.968 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:01.968 --> 00:00:03.936 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:03.936 --> 00:00:07.380 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:07.380 --> 00:00:15.440 align:middle line:90%


00:00:15.440 --> 00:00:19.790 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: But let me
just quickly review

00:00:19.790 --> 00:00:22.950 align:middle line:84%
some what we have done
so far in the class.

00:00:22.950 --> 00:00:32.304 align:middle line:84%
So first, we talked about R
as an ordered set and fields.

00:00:32.304 --> 00:00:36.470 align:middle line:90%


00:00:36.470 --> 00:00:39.805 align:middle line:84%
Then we have talked about
sequences and limits.

00:00:39.805 --> 00:00:49.730 align:middle line:90%


00:00:49.730 --> 00:00:51.523 align:middle line:90%
And then we talked about series.

00:00:51.523 --> 00:00:55.370 align:middle line:90%


00:00:55.370 --> 00:00:58.130 align:middle line:84%
And then, finally, we
have talked about--

00:00:58.130 --> 00:01:00.720 align:middle line:84%
and this is where we
will continue today--

00:01:00.720 --> 00:01:02.960 align:middle line:90%
we talked about metric spaces.

00:01:02.960 --> 00:01:06.810 align:middle line:90%


00:01:06.810 --> 00:01:13.770 align:middle line:84%
And so the idea here
is that we want to--

00:01:13.770 --> 00:01:20.760 align:middle line:84%
there's a lot of things from
R that actually generalize

00:01:20.760 --> 00:01:23.370 align:middle line:90%
and make sense.

00:01:23.370 --> 00:01:26.500 align:middle line:84%
And some of those are
sequences and limits.

00:01:26.500 --> 00:01:30.160 align:middle line:84%
So they generalize from
R to metric spaces.

00:01:30.160 --> 00:01:32.760 align:middle line:84%
There are other things
that don't generalize.

00:01:32.760 --> 00:01:33.940 align:middle line:90%
It's not an order.

00:01:33.940 --> 00:01:37.650 align:middle line:84%
A general metric space is
not-- it doesn't necessarily

00:01:37.650 --> 00:01:39.550 align:middle line:90%
come with an ordering.

00:01:39.550 --> 00:01:42.540 align:middle line:90%
And it's not like a field.

00:01:42.540 --> 00:01:48.190 align:middle line:84%
And in particular, typically,
you can't sum elements.

00:01:48.190 --> 00:01:51.490 align:middle line:84%
So a series doesn't
make sense either.

00:01:51.490 --> 00:01:56.700 align:middle line:84%
But these things here make
sense in a metric space.

00:01:56.700 --> 00:02:02.540 align:middle line:84%
And so let me just remind
you what is a metric space.

00:02:02.540 --> 00:02:12.270 align:middle line:90%
So a metric space is a set.

00:02:12.270 --> 00:02:14.750 align:middle line:90%
So x is a set.

00:02:14.750 --> 00:02:17.910 align:middle line:84%
And then there is a
distance function.

00:02:17.910 --> 00:02:24.680 align:middle line:84%
So this is a map from
x cross x into r.

00:02:24.680 --> 00:02:32.240 align:middle line:84%
And for each two pair
of elements x and y,

00:02:32.240 --> 00:02:35.760 align:middle line:90%
in x you have that--

00:02:35.760 --> 00:02:40.770 align:middle line:84%
let me make it a
capital X, like this.

00:02:40.770 --> 00:02:46.430 align:middle line:84%
For every two elements in this
set, the distance between them

00:02:46.430 --> 00:02:58.710 align:middle line:84%
should be positive and it should
be nonnegative and equal to 0.

00:02:58.710 --> 00:03:00.570 align:middle line:84%
The distance between
two points should

00:03:00.570 --> 00:03:06.240 align:middle line:84%
be 0 if and only if these
points are the same.

00:03:06.240 --> 00:03:10.030 align:middle line:90%
And then it should be symmetric.

00:03:10.030 --> 00:03:13.540 align:middle line:84%
So property 2 is that
it should be symmetric.

00:03:13.540 --> 00:03:18.870 align:middle line:84%
So it doesn't matter whether you
go from x to y or from y to x.

00:03:18.870 --> 00:03:20.360 align:middle line:90%
The distance is the same.

00:03:20.360 --> 00:03:23.520 align:middle line:90%


00:03:23.520 --> 00:03:28.560 align:middle line:84%
And the third, which is
the most nontrivial part,

00:03:28.560 --> 00:03:31.180 align:middle line:90%
is the triangle inequality.

00:03:31.180 --> 00:03:32.676 align:middle line:90%
So this here is symmetric.

00:03:32.676 --> 00:03:36.960 align:middle line:90%


00:03:36.960 --> 00:03:40.080 align:middle line:84%
And the third property
is that if you're

00:03:40.080 --> 00:03:45.000 align:middle line:84%
looking at x, y, and z,
so you have three points,

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:55.720 align:middle line:84%
and you go from x to C, then
it's certainly not further than

00:03:55.720 --> 00:04:01.820 align:middle line:84%
if you first go to from x to
y and then go from y to z.

00:04:01.820 --> 00:04:05.590 align:middle line:84%
So this should be less than or
equal to the distance from x

00:04:05.590 --> 00:04:09.760 align:middle line:84%
to y plus the
distance from y to z.

00:04:09.760 --> 00:04:14.080 align:middle line:84%
And so this third
property here is what's

00:04:14.080 --> 00:04:16.214 align:middle line:90%
called the triangle inequality.

00:04:16.214 --> 00:04:19.329 align:middle line:90%


00:04:19.329 --> 00:04:21.691 align:middle line:84%
So this is the
triangle inequality.

00:04:21.691 --> 00:04:29.560 align:middle line:90%


00:04:29.560 --> 00:04:34.760 align:middle line:84%
Now so that's what
a metric space is.

00:04:34.760 --> 00:04:44.680 align:middle line:84%
And again, so the canonical
example of a metric space

00:04:44.680 --> 00:04:49.310 align:middle line:84%
is where you're taking x
equal to the real numbers.

00:04:49.310 --> 00:04:52.630 align:middle line:84%
And then for two
true real numbers,

00:04:52.630 --> 00:04:54.660 align:middle line:84%
the distance between
them is just where

00:04:54.660 --> 00:04:58.950 align:middle line:84%
you're looking at the
norm of the difference.

00:04:58.950 --> 00:05:02.010 align:middle line:90%
So this here is a nice distance.

00:05:02.010 --> 00:05:03.910 align:middle line:90%
It's clearly nonnegative.

00:05:03.910 --> 00:05:08.530 align:middle line:84%
It's clearly equal to 0 if
and only if x is equal to y.

00:05:08.530 --> 00:05:10.240 align:middle line:90%
It's clearly symmetric.

00:05:10.240 --> 00:05:13.020 align:middle line:84%
And the triangle inequality
is this inequality

00:05:13.020 --> 00:05:14.655 align:middle line:90%
that we have used all the time.

00:05:14.655 --> 00:05:18.010 align:middle line:90%


00:05:18.010 --> 00:05:23.790 align:middle line:84%
So this here is slightly more
fancy version of the same

00:05:23.790 --> 00:05:28.530 align:middle line:90%
is where you're looking at R2.

00:05:28.530 --> 00:05:37.500 align:middle line:84%
So the x here is R2 Or it
could even be a general n.

00:05:37.500 --> 00:05:44.160 align:middle line:84%
And then if you think
about two elements in Rn

00:05:44.160 --> 00:05:48.540 align:middle line:84%
and you think about,
say, x here as--

00:05:48.540 --> 00:05:55.040 align:middle line:84%
it's written as
x1, x2, up to xn,

00:05:55.040 --> 00:05:58.540 align:middle line:84%
where each of these
xi's are in R,

00:05:58.540 --> 00:06:02.685 align:middle line:84%
and there are n many of
them, and likewise for y.

00:06:02.685 --> 00:06:09.520 align:middle line:90%


00:06:09.520 --> 00:06:14.830 align:middle line:84%
And then the distance
here the natural distance

00:06:14.830 --> 00:06:18.790 align:middle line:90%
is where you're taking--

00:06:18.790 --> 00:06:21.290 align:middle line:84%
this is what's called
the Euclidean distance.

00:06:21.290 --> 00:06:23.480 align:middle line:90%
It's given by Pythagoras.

00:06:23.480 --> 00:06:29.420 align:middle line:84%
And so it's the square root
of the sum of the squares,

00:06:29.420 --> 00:06:39.190 align:middle line:84%
so x1 minus y1 squared plus
x2 minus y2 squared plus

00:06:39.190 --> 00:06:46.200 align:middle line:84%
and then all the way up
to xn minus yn squared.

00:06:46.200 --> 00:06:48.890 align:middle line:90%


00:06:48.890 --> 00:06:53.600 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that if n
here is equal to 1, well,

00:06:53.600 --> 00:06:59.090 align:middle line:84%
then each element is just
a single element in R.

00:06:59.090 --> 00:07:03.170 align:middle line:84%
And so then this thing here
is really the same as that

00:07:03.170 --> 00:07:07.580 align:middle line:84%
because it's the
square of x minus y.

00:07:07.580 --> 00:07:09.413 align:middle line:84%
It's the square
of this distance.

00:07:09.413 --> 00:07:10.830 align:middle line:84%
And then you take
the square root.

00:07:10.830 --> 00:07:13.220 align:middle line:90%
So it's a norm.

00:07:13.220 --> 00:07:17.960 align:middle line:84%
So both of these is
called the Euclidean--

00:07:17.960 --> 00:07:20.470 align:middle line:84%
usually referred to as
a Euclidean distance.

00:07:20.470 --> 00:07:26.990 align:middle line:90%


00:07:26.990 --> 00:07:32.900 align:middle line:84%
So we looked at a
few other examples.

00:07:32.900 --> 00:07:38.600 align:middle line:84%
And I won't look at all of
them again, but just two more.

00:07:38.600 --> 00:07:41.155 align:middle line:84%
One is this with
the box distance.

00:07:41.155 --> 00:07:45.350 align:middle line:90%


00:07:45.350 --> 00:07:50.210 align:middle line:84%
And let me state it only
in R2, but just like this,

00:07:50.210 --> 00:07:52.340 align:middle line:90%
you could state it in any Rn.

00:07:52.340 --> 00:08:00.440 align:middle line:84%
So the spaces are true, and the
distance between two elements--

00:08:00.440 --> 00:08:02.270 align:middle line:90%
so again, we write it like this.

00:08:02.270 --> 00:08:05.710 align:middle line:84%
And we think about x
as being x1 comma x2,

00:08:05.710 --> 00:08:11.800 align:middle line:84%
where these are real numbers,
y equal to y1 comma y2.

00:08:11.800 --> 00:08:20.110 align:middle line:84%
And then this distance here
is the sum of these distances.

00:08:20.110 --> 00:08:26.590 align:middle line:84%
So this is a plus x2
minus y2, like that.

00:08:26.590 --> 00:08:29.210 align:middle line:84%
And this is clearly,
again, symmetric.

00:08:29.210 --> 00:08:30.800 align:middle line:90%
It's clearly nonnegative.

00:08:30.800 --> 00:08:36.679 align:middle line:84%
It's clearly equal to 0 if and
only if x and y are the same.

00:08:36.679 --> 00:08:39.280 align:middle line:84%
And the triangle
inequality-- well, that just

00:08:39.280 --> 00:08:43.360 align:middle line:84%
follows quite easily from
the triangle inequality

00:08:43.360 --> 00:08:46.730 align:middle line:90%
for this distance.

00:08:46.730 --> 00:08:49.440 align:middle line:90%
Then there is one more example.

00:08:49.440 --> 00:08:51.800 align:middle line:90%
I mean, there's other--

00:08:51.800 --> 00:08:54.410 align:middle line:84%
but there's one more
example that is often

00:08:54.410 --> 00:08:56.390 align:middle line:90%
useful to keep in mind.

00:08:56.390 --> 00:09:01.670 align:middle line:84%
And this is the last
one I will review.

00:09:01.670 --> 00:09:05.340 align:middle line:84%
And so this is the
continuous function.

00:09:05.340 --> 00:09:14.690 align:middle line:84%
So if you take an interval
a and b are real numbers,

00:09:14.690 --> 00:09:16.490 align:middle line:84%
and you're looking
at the interval

00:09:16.490 --> 00:09:20.490 align:middle line:84%
from a to b where both
endpoints are included,

00:09:20.490 --> 00:09:23.660 align:middle line:84%
and then you look at
the continuous function

00:09:23.660 --> 00:09:26.660 align:middle line:90%
on this interval.

00:09:26.660 --> 00:09:32.450 align:middle line:84%
And then if you have
two elements f and g--

00:09:32.450 --> 00:09:34.140 align:middle line:90%
so these are continuous.

00:09:34.140 --> 00:09:38.330 align:middle line:84%
Each of them are
continuous functions.

00:09:38.330 --> 00:09:43.350 align:middle line:84%
Then the distance between
these two continuous functions

00:09:43.350 --> 00:09:51.030 align:middle line:84%
is equal to the
max over x And then

00:09:51.030 --> 00:09:57.450 align:middle line:84%
f of x minus g of x,
right then, so x here

00:09:57.450 --> 00:09:59.711 align:middle line:90%
is in the interval from a to b.

00:09:59.711 --> 00:10:03.990 align:middle line:90%


00:10:03.990 --> 00:10:06.640 align:middle line:90%
And so this thing here--

00:10:06.640 --> 00:10:09.780 align:middle line:84%
so this here was on the midterm,
this particular example.

00:10:09.780 --> 00:10:14.310 align:middle line:84%
And this thing here
that the max is achieved

00:10:14.310 --> 00:10:17.640 align:middle line:84%
is just like if you're looking
at these two functions, then

00:10:17.640 --> 00:10:20.890 align:middle line:84%
this is the difference
between the two functions.

00:10:20.890 --> 00:10:23.170 align:middle line:90%
So this is also continuous.

00:10:23.170 --> 00:10:26.400 align:middle line:84%
And this means that the
maximum at the minimum

00:10:26.400 --> 00:10:28.890 align:middle line:84%
by the extreme value
theorem is achieved

00:10:28.890 --> 00:10:30.810 align:middle line:90%
on an interval of this form.

00:10:30.810 --> 00:10:34.470 align:middle line:84%
So this thing here
is really achieved,

00:10:34.470 --> 00:10:38.050 align:middle line:90%
and it's clearly nonnegative.

00:10:38.050 --> 00:10:41.750 align:middle line:84%
And it's easy to see that
it has the other property

00:10:41.750 --> 00:10:43.460 align:middle line:90%
of a metric space.

00:10:43.460 --> 00:10:47.300 align:middle line:84%
So these are just the
examples that we talked about.

00:10:47.300 --> 00:10:51.260 align:middle line:90%
And I just want to remind you.

00:10:51.260 --> 00:10:58.970 align:middle line:84%
And so then the question
is what generalizes from--

00:10:58.970 --> 00:11:03.870 align:middle line:84%
so we started with a
class talking about R.

00:11:03.870 --> 00:11:07.290 align:middle line:90%
And so it was an order field.

00:11:07.290 --> 00:11:08.870 align:middle line:84%
But a lot of the
things we talked

00:11:08.870 --> 00:11:11.180 align:middle line:84%
about for R, the
subsequent things

00:11:11.180 --> 00:11:16.340 align:middle line:84%
we talked about, sequences and
limits, they, as we will see,

00:11:16.340 --> 00:11:21.110 align:middle line:84%
make total sense in a
general metric space

00:11:21.110 --> 00:11:26.420 align:middle line:84%
and has important
consequences, including

00:11:26.420 --> 00:11:31.700 align:middle line:84%
to solve differential
equations and solving

00:11:31.700 --> 00:11:33.380 align:middle line:84%
all kinds of
equations, including

00:11:33.380 --> 00:11:35.900 align:middle line:90%
differential equations.

00:11:35.900 --> 00:11:44.190 align:middle line:84%
So now let me remind you
also, so we talked about that

00:11:44.190 --> 00:11:54.575 align:middle line:84%
if this is a metric space, then
a sequence in a metric space.

00:11:54.575 --> 00:11:59.550 align:middle line:90%


00:11:59.550 --> 00:12:01.852 align:middle line:90%
This is just a map.

00:12:01.852 --> 00:12:10.170 align:middle line:84%
This is a map from the
natural numbers into x.

00:12:10.170 --> 00:12:14.190 align:middle line:84%
So a sequence is
like a map like this.

00:12:14.190 --> 00:12:17.790 align:middle line:84%
And so usually,
the image of the n

00:12:17.790 --> 00:12:22.800 align:middle line:84%
element, this we will typically
denote, again, like this, xn.

00:12:22.800 --> 00:12:25.740 align:middle line:90%
So this is what a sequence is.

00:12:25.740 --> 00:12:35.610 align:middle line:84%
A subsequence-- this is
defined very similar to what

00:12:35.610 --> 00:12:37.880 align:middle line:90%
we did on the real line.

00:12:37.880 --> 00:12:41.680 align:middle line:84%
So a subsequence
is the composition

00:12:41.680 --> 00:13:06.700 align:middle line:84%
of f with a strictly increasing
map g from the natural numbers

00:13:06.700 --> 00:13:08.620 align:middle line:90%
into n.

00:13:08.620 --> 00:13:13.600 align:middle line:84%
And then the sequence
is then where

00:13:13.600 --> 00:13:16.660 align:middle line:84%
you're looking where
you apply first g,

00:13:16.660 --> 00:13:20.090 align:middle line:90%
and then you apply the f.

00:13:20.090 --> 00:13:24.340 align:middle line:84%
So when you first
apply g, then it

00:13:24.340 --> 00:13:26.270 align:middle line:84%
gives you another
natural number.

00:13:26.270 --> 00:13:28.600 align:middle line:84%
And so this thing
here, the image of this

00:13:28.600 --> 00:13:30.760 align:middle line:90%
is then a element in x.

00:13:30.760 --> 00:13:32.650 align:middle line:90%
So that's a subsequence.

00:13:32.650 --> 00:13:35.150 align:middle line:84%
And again, this was
strictly increasing

00:13:35.150 --> 00:13:39.750 align:middle line:84%
guarantee you that the elements
appear in the same order.

00:13:39.750 --> 00:13:41.580 align:middle line:84%
You're picking a
selection of them,

00:13:41.580 --> 00:13:43.160 align:middle line:84%
but they appear
in the same order

00:13:43.160 --> 00:13:44.770 align:middle line:90%
as in the original sequence.

00:13:44.770 --> 00:13:48.230 align:middle line:90%


00:13:48.230 --> 00:13:51.670 align:middle line:84%
So sequences and
subsequences make sense.

00:13:51.670 --> 00:13:54.530 align:middle line:90%


00:13:54.530 --> 00:13:56.667 align:middle line:90%
We can then also talk about--

00:13:56.667 --> 00:13:58.250 align:middle line:84%
and I know we talked
about, but I just

00:13:58.250 --> 00:14:00.200 align:middle line:84%
want to-- because
of the break, I just

00:14:00.200 --> 00:14:05.120 align:middle line:84%
want to review quickly a
few of the things we talked

00:14:05.120 --> 00:14:07.610 align:middle line:90%
about right before the break.

00:14:07.610 --> 00:14:22.390 align:middle line:84%
So one is that a convergent
sequence in a metric space--

00:14:22.390 --> 00:14:26.810 align:middle line:90%


00:14:26.810 --> 00:14:33.640 align:middle line:84%
so if this here is a
metric space and xn

00:14:33.640 --> 00:14:49.390 align:middle line:84%
is a sequence in xd,
then we say that we

00:14:49.390 --> 00:15:02.595 align:middle line:84%
say that xn converges to
x if the following hold.

00:15:02.595 --> 00:15:10.870 align:middle line:90%


00:15:10.870 --> 00:15:21.310 align:middle line:84%
That for all epsilon
greater than 0,

00:15:21.310 --> 00:15:33.320 align:middle line:84%
there exists capital N
such that if little n is

00:15:33.320 --> 00:15:40.340 align:middle line:84%
equal to capital N, then
xn the distance between xn

00:15:40.340 --> 00:15:45.440 align:middle line:84%
and this limit should
be less than epsilon.

00:15:45.440 --> 00:15:49.790 align:middle line:84%
So that's exact parallel
to how we defined

00:15:49.790 --> 00:15:53.660 align:middle line:84%
the limit of a sequence or
that a sequence is converging

00:15:53.660 --> 00:15:56.930 align:middle line:90%
if it was a sequence in R.

00:15:56.930 --> 00:16:03.320 align:middle line:84%
And likewise, we can define
a sequence in a metric space.

00:16:03.320 --> 00:16:22.670 align:middle line:84%
So we define a Cauchy sequence
in a metric space x, d.

00:16:22.670 --> 00:16:26.460 align:middle line:84%
So this is a sequence
so that for all--

00:16:26.460 --> 00:16:35.460 align:middle line:84%
so this is a sequence
xn in such that

00:16:35.460 --> 00:16:41.040 align:middle line:84%
for all epsilon
greater than 0, there

00:16:41.040 --> 00:16:54.930 align:middle line:84%
exists a capital N such that
if little m and little n

00:16:54.930 --> 00:16:58.390 align:middle line:84%
are bigger or
equal to capital N.

00:16:58.390 --> 00:17:00.210 align:middle line:84%
So remember that
a Cauchy sequence

00:17:00.210 --> 00:17:03.190 align:middle line:84%
means that the tail
is bunching together.

00:17:03.190 --> 00:17:06.240 align:middle line:84%
So this means that if you
are sufficiently far out,

00:17:06.240 --> 00:17:13.770 align:middle line:84%
then these elements, xn and
xm, are epsilon close together.

00:17:13.770 --> 00:17:17.520 align:middle line:84%
So this is what it
means for a sequence

00:17:17.520 --> 00:17:20.609 align:middle line:90%
to be a Cauchy sequence.

00:17:20.609 --> 00:17:25.050 align:middle line:84%
And so now we have
this theorem, and I

00:17:25.050 --> 00:17:27.670 align:middle line:84%
think I mentioned
it before the break.

00:17:27.670 --> 00:17:29.780 align:middle line:84%
But let's just
quickly run through it

00:17:29.780 --> 00:17:31.940 align:middle line:90%
because it's very short.

00:17:31.940 --> 00:17:39.530 align:middle line:84%
So if you have a-- so if
this is a metric space,

00:17:39.530 --> 00:17:57.830 align:middle line:84%
then the theorem is that any
convergent sequence is also

00:17:57.830 --> 00:17:58.810 align:middle line:90%
a Cauchy sequence.

00:17:58.810 --> 00:18:06.140 align:middle line:90%


00:18:06.140 --> 00:18:08.005 align:middle line:90%
And the proof is like this.

00:18:08.005 --> 00:18:10.850 align:middle line:90%


00:18:10.850 --> 00:18:25.680 align:middle line:84%
So given epsilon, since xn
is a convergent sequence,

00:18:25.680 --> 00:18:28.680 align:middle line:84%
so you assume that x is a
convergence sequence-- let's

00:18:28.680 --> 00:18:30.100 align:middle line:90%
call the limit x.

00:18:30.100 --> 00:18:35.430 align:middle line:84%
Since xn converges
to x, this means

00:18:35.430 --> 00:18:49.590 align:middle line:84%
that there exists capital N
such that if little n is bigger

00:18:49.590 --> 00:18:53.610 align:middle line:84%
or equal to capital N, then
the distance between little

00:18:53.610 --> 00:19:03.390 align:middle line:84%
x, little n, and nx here, this
distance here is less than--

00:19:03.390 --> 00:19:07.200 align:middle line:90%
and then I use epsilon over 2.

00:19:07.200 --> 00:19:15.570 align:middle line:84%
And so this means
that, therefore,

00:19:15.570 --> 00:19:23.220 align:middle line:84%
if little m and little n are
both bigger than capital N then

00:19:23.220 --> 00:19:26.470 align:middle line:90%
the distance between the two--

00:19:26.470 --> 00:19:30.610 align:middle line:84%
distance between these
two elements here,

00:19:30.610 --> 00:19:33.790 align:middle line:84%
well, by the
triangle inequality,

00:19:33.790 --> 00:19:36.830 align:middle line:84%
we have that this
distance is less than

00:19:36.830 --> 00:19:42.820 align:middle line:84%
if you go over the point x, so
if you go from xn to x and then

00:19:42.820 --> 00:19:46.480 align:middle line:90%
from x to xm like that.

00:19:46.480 --> 00:19:54.400 align:middle line:84%
But each of these, because
both of these, both little m

00:19:54.400 --> 00:19:57.260 align:middle line:84%
and little n are
bigger than capital N,

00:19:57.260 --> 00:20:03.010 align:middle line:84%
then both of these distances
are bounded by epsilon over 2.

00:20:03.010 --> 00:20:07.340 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that this thing
here is smaller than epsilon.

00:20:07.340 --> 00:20:10.120 align:middle line:84%
So this proved that
in a metric space,

00:20:10.120 --> 00:20:14.470 align:middle line:84%
any convergent sequence
is also a Cauchy sequence.

00:20:14.470 --> 00:20:21.670 align:middle line:84%
And so we know that
if the metric space is

00:20:21.670 --> 00:20:26.550 align:middle line:84%
R with the usual
Euclidean distance,

00:20:26.550 --> 00:20:30.300 align:middle line:84%
then actually, you
also-- and that

00:20:30.300 --> 00:20:33.005 align:middle line:84%
was the convergence
theorem, so the Cauchy.

00:20:33.005 --> 00:20:35.640 align:middle line:90%


00:20:35.640 --> 00:20:36.755 align:middle line:90%
convergence theorem.

00:20:36.755 --> 00:20:41.310 align:middle line:90%


00:20:41.310 --> 00:20:51.840 align:middle line:84%
So Cauchy convergence theorem--
it said that if x comma d is R

00:20:51.840 --> 00:20:56.580 align:middle line:84%
with the Euclidean distance-- so
I denote the Euclidean distance

00:20:56.580 --> 00:20:59.340 align:middle line:90%
like this--

00:20:59.340 --> 00:21:02.750 align:middle line:90%
then we have the converse.

00:21:02.750 --> 00:21:11.550 align:middle line:90%


00:21:11.550 --> 00:21:14.222 align:middle line:90%
So i.e.

00:21:14.222 --> 00:21:18.520 align:middle line:90%
that any Cauchy sequence--

00:21:18.520 --> 00:21:24.130 align:middle line:90%


00:21:24.130 --> 00:21:27.320 align:middle line:90%
this is also convergent.

00:21:27.320 --> 00:21:37.258 align:middle line:90%


00:21:37.258 --> 00:21:42.410 align:middle line:84%
Now we looked at a
very simple example.

00:21:42.410 --> 00:21:46.790 align:middle line:84%
And if I have time, I will
talk about it a little bit more

00:21:46.790 --> 00:21:49.810 align:middle line:90%
interesting example.

00:21:49.810 --> 00:21:54.230 align:middle line:84%
Otherwise, I'll talk
about that next time.

00:21:54.230 --> 00:22:00.940 align:middle line:84%
So if the metric space was R
with the Euclidean distance,

00:22:00.940 --> 00:22:05.570 align:middle line:84%
but then we had a converse-- but
if the metric space was, say--

00:22:05.570 --> 00:22:08.510 align:middle line:84%
so we looked at where
the metric space was--

00:22:08.510 --> 00:22:13.400 align:middle line:84%
so where x here, the set was
the interval from 0 to 1,

00:22:13.400 --> 00:22:18.620 align:middle line:84%
and the distance here was just
the usual Euclidean distance.

00:22:18.620 --> 00:22:27.290 align:middle line:84%
So then if you're looking at
the sequence xn, 1 over n,

00:22:27.290 --> 00:22:32.340 align:middle line:84%
this one here, this is a
sequence in this space.

00:22:32.340 --> 00:22:34.640 align:middle line:90%
It's a Cauchy sequence.

00:22:34.640 --> 00:22:37.880 align:middle line:84%
But it doesn't
converge in this space

00:22:37.880 --> 00:22:42.140 align:middle line:84%
because 0 is not
part of the space.

00:22:42.140 --> 00:22:46.490 align:middle line:84%
So this here is a
Cauchy sequence.

00:22:46.490 --> 00:22:51.720 align:middle line:84%
So you may say this is a
rather trivial example,

00:22:51.720 --> 00:22:54.860 align:middle line:90%
not very interesting.

00:22:54.860 --> 00:22:59.510 align:middle line:84%
I'll show you another example
a little bit later or next time

00:22:59.510 --> 00:23:04.280 align:middle line:84%
that is more interesting
but, in some sense,

00:23:04.280 --> 00:23:07.790 align:middle line:84%
has some of the same feature,
that the space is just not

00:23:07.790 --> 00:23:09.450 align:middle line:90%
quite large enough.

00:23:09.450 --> 00:23:11.510 align:middle line:84%
But it will seem
more interesting.

00:23:11.510 --> 00:23:18.560 align:middle line:84%
So this here is a Cauchy
sequence that is not convergent.

00:23:18.560 --> 00:23:23.590 align:middle line:90%


00:23:23.590 --> 00:23:32.110 align:middle line:84%
So again, the Cauchy
[INAUDIBLE], so this

00:23:32.110 --> 00:23:34.030 align:middle line:90%
leads to the following.

00:23:34.030 --> 00:23:36.570 align:middle line:84%
This leads to the
following notion here.

00:23:36.570 --> 00:23:45.520 align:middle line:90%


00:23:45.520 --> 00:23:47.530 align:middle line:84%
So this is the
following definition

00:23:47.530 --> 00:23:52.923 align:middle line:90%
of being Cauchy complete.

00:23:52.923 --> 00:23:57.400 align:middle line:90%


00:23:57.400 --> 00:24:01.090 align:middle line:84%
So a space or metric
space x comma d

00:24:01.090 --> 00:24:22.876 align:middle line:84%
is Cauchy complete if every
Cauchy sequence is convergent.

00:24:22.876 --> 00:24:33.630 align:middle line:90%


00:24:33.630 --> 00:24:38.700 align:middle line:90%
So now let me define some--

00:24:38.700 --> 00:24:44.930 align:middle line:84%
so if we begin with extending
some notions from our--

00:24:44.930 --> 00:24:47.600 align:middle line:84%
so the first one
I want to extend

00:24:47.600 --> 00:24:52.150 align:middle line:84%
is what it means in a metric
space, what is a form?

00:24:52.150 --> 00:24:59.600 align:middle line:90%


00:24:59.600 --> 00:25:04.040 align:middle line:90%
So we have here--

00:25:04.040 --> 00:25:05.650 align:middle line:90%
so a metric form.

00:25:05.650 --> 00:25:10.160 align:middle line:90%


00:25:10.160 --> 00:25:13.590 align:middle line:90%
So we have a metric space.

00:25:13.590 --> 00:25:17.710 align:middle line:84%
We have a point in
the metric space.

00:25:17.710 --> 00:25:23.970 align:middle line:84%
We have some r which is a real
number, positive real number.

00:25:23.970 --> 00:25:29.700 align:middle line:84%
And then we define
a Br of x here.

00:25:29.700 --> 00:25:41.610 align:middle line:84%
This here is the set y in x So
that the distance from x to y

00:25:41.610 --> 00:25:44.160 align:middle line:84%
is less than or
strictly less than r.

00:25:44.160 --> 00:25:49.830 align:middle line:90%


00:25:49.830 --> 00:25:53.730 align:middle line:84%
And so this here is called this
here is called the metric ball.

00:25:53.730 --> 00:25:57.630 align:middle line:84%
This set here is called
a metric ball or just

00:25:57.630 --> 00:26:11.680 align:middle line:90%
a ball with radius r and set x.

00:26:11.680 --> 00:26:18.440 align:middle line:90%


00:26:18.440 --> 00:26:25.230 align:middle line:90%
Now let me just illustrate it.

00:26:25.230 --> 00:26:27.960 align:middle line:84%
So a lot of the intuitions
about metric spaces--

00:26:27.960 --> 00:26:31.940 align:middle line:84%
but you have to be careful
because, sometimes,

00:26:31.940 --> 00:26:36.980 align:middle line:84%
that intuition fools you just
because metric spaces are

00:26:36.980 --> 00:26:38.880 align:middle line:90%
allowed to be very general.

00:26:38.880 --> 00:26:41.600 align:middle line:84%
But a lot of the intuition
about metric spaces

00:26:41.600 --> 00:26:46.560 align:middle line:84%
come from just thinking about
things in Euclidean space.

00:26:46.560 --> 00:26:49.790 align:middle line:84%
So when I'm talking
about Euclidean space,

00:26:49.790 --> 00:26:53.340 align:middle line:84%
I'm thinking mostly about
it could be on the line.

00:26:53.340 --> 00:26:57.920 align:middle line:84%
So in the case where x is
r or it could be in a plane

00:26:57.920 --> 00:27:02.730 align:middle line:84%
where x is r2, or it
could be where x is r3.

00:27:02.730 --> 00:27:05.490 align:middle line:84%
And so in either of
those three cases,

00:27:05.490 --> 00:27:08.810 align:middle line:84%
the distance is the distance
that you're used to,

00:27:08.810 --> 00:27:12.630 align:middle line:84%
which is the Euclidean
distance we talked about.

00:27:12.630 --> 00:27:18.130 align:middle line:84%
And so in that case, if
you take a point here--

00:27:18.130 --> 00:27:21.510 align:middle line:84%
so just thinking
about the example

00:27:21.510 --> 00:27:24.210 align:middle line:84%
where you think about
the example where

00:27:24.210 --> 00:27:28.360 align:middle line:90%
x is R2, then a ball here--

00:27:28.360 --> 00:27:31.920 align:middle line:84%
well, a usual ball is
really just everything

00:27:31.920 --> 00:27:35.610 align:middle line:90%
that is the distance r from x.

00:27:35.610 --> 00:27:38.410 align:middle line:84%
So this is kind of what
I defined over here.

00:27:38.410 --> 00:27:44.440 align:middle line:84%
There's another thing you could
also look at some other sets.

00:27:44.440 --> 00:27:52.050 align:middle line:84%
So imagine that you take
a line in the plane,

00:27:52.050 --> 00:27:56.850 align:middle line:84%
and you could look at-- or
Maybe this could even be--

00:27:56.850 --> 00:27:58.530 align:middle line:84%
it would look more
interesting if I'm

00:27:58.530 --> 00:28:02.070 align:middle line:90%
thinking about a line in R3.

00:28:02.070 --> 00:28:04.920 align:middle line:84%
So imagine that
this is now-- this

00:28:04.920 --> 00:28:07.090 align:middle line:90%
is supposed to look like in R3.

00:28:07.090 --> 00:28:08.920 align:middle line:84%
And then you could
look at a line,

00:28:08.920 --> 00:28:13.310 align:middle line:84%
and you could look at-- instead
of looking at a metric ball,

00:28:13.310 --> 00:28:16.040 align:middle line:84%
you could look at a
tubular neighborhood.

00:28:16.040 --> 00:28:17.810 align:middle line:90%
So suppose you're looking at--

00:28:17.810 --> 00:28:19.335 align:middle line:90%
that's very similar to a ball.

00:28:19.335 --> 00:28:27.850 align:middle line:90%


00:28:27.850 --> 00:28:33.080 align:middle line:84%
So a tubular neighborhood, let's
say a r tubular neighborhood--

00:28:33.080 --> 00:28:36.700 align:middle line:84%
this is where have
some positive number r

00:28:36.700 --> 00:28:43.150 align:middle line:84%
and you're looking at everything
that has distance at most

00:28:43.150 --> 00:28:46.970 align:middle line:84%
or let's say strictly less
than r from this line.

00:28:46.970 --> 00:28:49.180 align:middle line:84%
So if you do that,
that would look

00:28:49.180 --> 00:28:52.600 align:middle line:84%
like a cylinder, where the
boundary of the cylinder

00:28:52.600 --> 00:28:56.200 align:middle line:84%
is not included because I
require things to have distance

00:28:56.200 --> 00:28:59.920 align:middle line:90%
strictly less than r.

00:28:59.920 --> 00:29:05.700 align:middle line:84%
This here would be a r tubular
neighborhood of a line.

00:29:05.700 --> 00:29:11.050 align:middle line:84%
So this is just to say that
of notion here of a ball,

00:29:11.050 --> 00:29:13.690 align:middle line:84%
you could even have
something more general.

00:29:13.690 --> 00:29:17.610 align:middle line:84%
And both of these things
that you know well

00:29:17.610 --> 00:29:20.430 align:middle line:84%
from Euclidean space,
they make sense

00:29:20.430 --> 00:29:22.545 align:middle line:90%
in just a general metric space.

00:29:22.545 --> 00:29:25.140 align:middle line:84%
The line maybe
doesn't make sense.

00:29:25.140 --> 00:29:28.380 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes, often,
it does, actually.

00:29:28.380 --> 00:29:30.700 align:middle line:84%
But that's something
more complicated.

00:29:30.700 --> 00:29:33.430 align:middle line:84%
But you could just think
about it as a subset.

00:29:33.430 --> 00:29:37.560 align:middle line:84%
And then [? things ?] that have
distance strictly less than r

00:29:37.560 --> 00:29:38.355 align:middle line:90%
to that subset.

00:29:38.355 --> 00:29:44.530 align:middle line:90%


00:29:44.530 --> 00:29:48.324 align:middle line:90%
So this is what it means for--

00:29:48.324 --> 00:29:52.620 align:middle line:84%
this is what a ball
is, metric ball.

00:29:52.620 --> 00:29:57.930 align:middle line:84%
Then there's the notion of a
subset of a metric space being

00:29:57.930 --> 00:30:01.610 align:middle line:90%
bounded, so a bounded subset.

00:30:01.610 --> 00:30:06.400 align:middle line:90%


00:30:06.400 --> 00:30:09.880 align:middle line:90%
So there's another definition--

00:30:09.880 --> 00:30:20.595 align:middle line:84%
bounded subset of
a metric space.

00:30:20.595 --> 00:30:27.820 align:middle line:90%


00:30:27.820 --> 00:30:31.480 align:middle line:90%
So we have a metric space here.

00:30:31.480 --> 00:30:35.890 align:middle line:90%
And we have A as a subset.

00:30:35.890 --> 00:30:56.260 align:middle line:84%
And we say that A
is bounded if there

00:30:56.260 --> 00:31:02.585 align:middle line:84%
exists x, an element in
this metric space, and d--

00:31:02.585 --> 00:31:05.400 align:middle line:90%


00:31:05.400 --> 00:31:14.270 align:middle line:84%
d is some positive real
number such that A here

00:31:14.270 --> 00:31:21.205 align:middle line:84%
is contained in the ball
of radius d centered at x.

00:31:21.205 --> 00:31:25.976 align:middle line:90%


00:31:25.976 --> 00:31:30.980 align:middle line:84%
Now with this-- so there's
a few things like this

00:31:30.980 --> 00:31:34.770 align:middle line:90%
that we'll see for these things.

00:31:34.770 --> 00:31:39.500 align:middle line:84%
The empty set-- if you
take x and you take

00:31:39.500 --> 00:31:43.255 align:middle line:84%
the subset that has no
elements, that's the empty set.

00:31:43.255 --> 00:31:45.830 align:middle line:90%


00:31:45.830 --> 00:31:49.190 align:middle line:84%
The empty set is
contained in everything.

00:31:49.190 --> 00:31:52.190 align:middle line:84%
So actually, the empty
set would be bounded.

00:31:52.190 --> 00:31:57.920 align:middle line:84%
But it's not a particularly
interesting example

00:31:57.920 --> 00:31:58.910 align:middle line:90%
of a bounded set.

00:31:58.910 --> 00:32:03.340 align:middle line:84%
And it may be that the whole
metric space is possible

00:32:03.340 --> 00:32:06.010 align:middle line:84%
that the whole metric
space is bounded

00:32:06.010 --> 00:32:09.110 align:middle line:90%
if it was like an interval.

00:32:09.110 --> 00:32:12.230 align:middle line:84%
If it was just an
interval where both--

00:32:12.230 --> 00:32:14.500 align:middle line:84%
so suppose you have
some interval from A

00:32:14.500 --> 00:32:18.580 align:middle line:90%
to B. Then this thing here is--

00:32:18.580 --> 00:32:22.480 align:middle line:84%
if you think about the usual
distance on that interval,

00:32:22.480 --> 00:32:25.120 align:middle line:90%
then that's a bounded set.

00:32:25.120 --> 00:32:27.010 align:middle line:90%
The whole set x is bounded.

00:32:27.010 --> 00:32:32.230 align:middle line:84%
So in particular, any subset
would also be bounded.

00:32:32.230 --> 00:32:40.300 align:middle line:84%
So now let me just prove
one theorem, one lemma, that

00:32:40.300 --> 00:32:44.930 align:middle line:84%
is another thing that
generalizes from R.

00:32:44.930 --> 00:32:48.230 align:middle line:84%
And that is that if you
take a Cauchy sequence--

00:32:48.230 --> 00:32:51.730 align:middle line:84%
so any Cauchy
sequence is bounded.

00:32:51.730 --> 00:32:53.265 align:middle line:90%
So let's prove this.

00:32:53.265 --> 00:32:57.770 align:middle line:90%


00:32:57.770 --> 00:33:05.750 align:middle line:84%
So we have, again,
a metric space.

00:33:05.750 --> 00:33:08.755 align:middle line:90%
xn is a Cauchy sequence.

00:33:08.755 --> 00:33:16.130 align:middle line:90%


00:33:16.130 --> 00:33:23.990 align:middle line:84%
And then we think about
the set xn minus--

00:33:23.990 --> 00:33:27.870 align:middle line:90%
so this is this subset of x.

00:33:27.870 --> 00:33:32.940 align:middle line:84%
And I claim that this subset
here, this subset here--

00:33:32.940 --> 00:33:35.965 align:middle line:90%
so A here is bounded.

00:33:35.965 --> 00:33:40.760 align:middle line:90%


00:33:40.760 --> 00:33:43.923 align:middle line:90%
Now why is that the case?

00:33:43.923 --> 00:33:49.760 align:middle line:90%


00:33:49.760 --> 00:34:04.980 align:middle line:84%
So since xn is a sequence,
if I choose epsilon with--

00:34:04.980 --> 00:34:10.770 align:middle line:84%
so with epsilon,
say, equal to 1,

00:34:10.770 --> 00:34:22.920 align:middle line:84%
you have that there exists
capital N so that if little n--

00:34:22.920 --> 00:34:29.520 align:middle line:84%
such that if little
n and little m

00:34:29.520 --> 00:34:34.050 align:middle line:84%
bigger than capital N, then
the distance between the two

00:34:34.050 --> 00:34:39.760 align:middle line:90%
is smaller than 1.

00:34:39.760 --> 00:34:42.210 align:middle line:84%
This is just using that
as a Cauchy sequence

00:34:42.210 --> 00:34:48.179 align:middle line:84%
and just using one particular
epsilon, namely taking epsilon

00:34:48.179 --> 00:34:51.360 align:middle line:90%
to be equal to 1.

00:34:51.360 --> 00:34:53.850 align:middle line:90%
So now, of course, this means--

00:34:53.850 --> 00:34:57.720 align:middle line:84%
and now you don't need
this event for all of this.

00:34:57.720 --> 00:35:00.180 align:middle line:90%
You don't need it like this.

00:35:00.180 --> 00:35:06.830 align:middle line:84%
So in particular,
therefore, as long

00:35:06.830 --> 00:35:11.210 align:middle line:84%
as n is bigger than capital
N, well, you can use one--

00:35:11.210 --> 00:35:13.550 align:middle line:90%
or you can use m here.

00:35:13.550 --> 00:35:17.130 align:middle line:90%
You can use capital N for m.

00:35:17.130 --> 00:35:19.160 align:middle line:84%
So then this here--
say, therefore,

00:35:19.160 --> 00:35:26.690 align:middle line:84%
for little n bigger than this,
we have that this thing here,

00:35:26.690 --> 00:35:29.570 align:middle line:84%
the distance to this
is smaller than 1.

00:35:29.570 --> 00:35:33.620 align:middle line:90%


00:35:33.620 --> 00:35:41.870 align:middle line:84%
And so now you have
that if you now

00:35:41.870 --> 00:35:52.380 align:middle line:84%
set r equal to 1 plus the
maximum of the distance

00:35:52.380 --> 00:36:07.110 align:middle line:84%
from xN, x capital N,
to xi, where i here runs

00:36:07.110 --> 00:36:11.410 align:middle line:90%
from 1 of 2 capital N minus 1.

00:36:11.410 --> 00:36:17.310 align:middle line:84%
So there are n minus 1 of these
that you take the maximum over.

00:36:17.310 --> 00:36:22.710 align:middle line:84%
So if you define little r to
be like this, then obviously,

00:36:22.710 --> 00:36:24.700 align:middle line:84%
little r is some
positive number.

00:36:24.700 --> 00:36:25.830 align:middle line:90%
It's finite.

00:36:25.830 --> 00:36:31.620 align:middle line:90%


00:36:31.620 --> 00:36:37.170 align:middle line:84%
And now I claim that our set A
here is contained in this ball

00:36:37.170 --> 00:36:39.850 align:middle line:90%
here around xn.

00:36:39.850 --> 00:36:42.900 align:middle line:90%
So I claim this thing here.

00:36:42.900 --> 00:36:57.190 align:middle line:90%


00:36:57.190 --> 00:36:58.070 align:middle line:90%
Now let's see.

00:36:58.070 --> 00:37:00.580 align:middle line:90%
So why is this the case?

00:37:00.580 --> 00:37:06.050 align:middle line:90%
So if x here--

00:37:06.050 --> 00:37:08.830 align:middle line:90%
so we need to prove that--

00:37:08.830 --> 00:37:24.070 align:middle line:84%
we need to show that
for all n you have

00:37:24.070 --> 00:37:31.840 align:middle line:84%
that the distance
here is less than r.

00:37:31.840 --> 00:37:34.870 align:middle line:84%
If that's the case,
then the whole set

00:37:34.870 --> 00:37:39.310 align:middle line:90%
here would lie in this ball.

00:37:39.310 --> 00:37:44.140 align:middle line:90%
But you see that if n here--

00:37:44.140 --> 00:37:50.470 align:middle line:84%
well, if n is bigger or equal
to capital N, but this--

00:37:50.470 --> 00:38:01.440 align:middle line:90%


00:38:01.440 --> 00:38:03.250 align:middle line:90%
so we need to show this in here.

00:38:03.250 --> 00:38:06.180 align:middle line:84%
If little n is bigger
than capital N,

00:38:06.180 --> 00:38:11.730 align:middle line:84%
then we have that the distance
from this little n to this one

00:38:11.730 --> 00:38:13.960 align:middle line:90%
here by the tail--

00:38:13.960 --> 00:38:16.320 align:middle line:90%
the tail was less than 1.

00:38:16.320 --> 00:38:21.510 align:middle line:84%
But this thing here is actually
why-- this is actually--

00:38:21.510 --> 00:38:25.930 align:middle line:84%
this is equal to r because
it was 1 plus this maximum.

00:38:25.930 --> 00:38:29.170 align:middle line:84%
And then this is maximum
over nonnegative numbers.

00:38:29.170 --> 00:38:36.720 align:middle line:84%
So you see that for the whole
tail, we have this property.

00:38:36.720 --> 00:38:43.150 align:middle line:84%
But for all the other
ones, for n less than

00:38:43.150 --> 00:38:50.440 align:middle line:84%
or equal less than n minus 1,
these are the remaining ones.

00:38:50.440 --> 00:39:00.530 align:middle line:84%
There, the distance from xn
to x capital N, where it's--

00:39:00.530 --> 00:39:02.810 align:middle line:90%
this is one of these guys.

00:39:02.810 --> 00:39:04.870 align:middle line:90%
So it's clearly this one here.

00:39:04.870 --> 00:39:09.800 align:middle line:84%
It's clearly less
than capital R.

00:39:09.800 --> 00:39:11.800 align:middle line:84%
And it's really
strictly less than

00:39:11.800 --> 00:39:13.460 align:middle line:90%
because there's this one also.

00:39:13.460 --> 00:39:14.650 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

00:39:14.650 --> 00:39:17.330 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] does
it has to be 1 plus the max,

00:39:17.330 --> 00:39:20.650 align:middle line:84%
or could it be the max of
1 or all of those elements

00:39:20.650 --> 00:39:22.810 align:middle line:90%
of the sequence?

00:39:22.810 --> 00:39:26.410 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: I wanted this
one here to be strict.

00:39:26.410 --> 00:39:28.040 align:middle line:90%
It's just a silly thing.

00:39:28.040 --> 00:39:30.670 align:middle line:84%
But that's why I
took it like that.

00:39:30.670 --> 00:39:32.450 align:middle line:84%
Because otherwise
this would be strict.

00:39:32.450 --> 00:39:38.190 align:middle line:84%
But it's just a trivial thing,
and it doesn't matter very much.

00:39:38.190 --> 00:39:40.190 align:middle line:84%
At this stage, it makes
no difference, actually.

00:39:40.190 --> 00:39:43.120 align:middle line:90%
But it was just to use this.

00:39:43.120 --> 00:39:45.020 align:middle line:84%
We'll talk a little bit
more about the balls

00:39:45.020 --> 00:39:50.420 align:middle line:84%
because there is another way
you could define the ball.

00:39:50.420 --> 00:39:52.480 align:middle line:84%
Maybe I'll say a few
words about that now.

00:39:52.480 --> 00:39:55.500 align:middle line:90%


00:39:55.500 --> 00:40:00.680 align:middle line:84%
So what this proves, again,
is that in any metric space,

00:40:00.680 --> 00:40:05.810 align:middle line:84%
a Cauchy sequence is
automatically bounded.

00:40:05.810 --> 00:40:07.640 align:middle line:84%
And so remember, in
any metric space,

00:40:07.640 --> 00:40:10.080 align:middle line:84%
a convergent sequence
is a Cauchy sequence.

00:40:10.080 --> 00:40:13.610 align:middle line:84%
So a convergent sequence
is also bounded.

00:40:13.610 --> 00:40:18.060 align:middle line:84%
And now there's this question,
which is a natural question,

00:40:18.060 --> 00:40:22.550 align:middle line:84%
and this is connected to
the definition of ball.

00:40:22.550 --> 00:40:26.030 align:middle line:84%
So the way we define-- and
it's actually worthwhile

00:40:26.030 --> 00:40:31.550 align:middle line:84%
emphasizing because it's
useful in the next thing

00:40:31.550 --> 00:40:34.280 align:middle line:90%
that we want to get to.

00:40:34.280 --> 00:40:39.860 align:middle line:84%
And so when I define
a ball, I assumed--

00:40:39.860 --> 00:40:45.360 align:middle line:84%
so the definition of the ball--
just write it up again here.

00:40:45.360 --> 00:40:48.780 align:middle line:84%
So the definition of a
ball in a metric space--

00:40:48.780 --> 00:40:56.550 align:middle line:84%
these are the y in this set so
that the distance to the center

00:40:56.550 --> 00:40:59.670 align:middle line:90%
is strictly less than r.

00:40:59.670 --> 00:41:05.070 align:middle line:84%
You could, of course, have
defined it differently.

00:41:05.070 --> 00:41:08.550 align:middle line:84%
You could define it
that this is strictly

00:41:08.550 --> 00:41:11.740 align:middle line:84%
less or is there strictly
less than or equal to--

00:41:11.740 --> 00:41:15.540 align:middle line:84%
I want to use
strictly less here.

00:41:15.540 --> 00:41:19.300 align:middle line:84%
But sometimes, if I
want to be very clear,

00:41:19.300 --> 00:41:21.970 align:middle line:84%
I will talk about
open and closed ball.

00:41:21.970 --> 00:41:24.010 align:middle line:84%
And this is what
we're getting to next.

00:41:24.010 --> 00:41:26.470 align:middle line:84%
And so when I'm talking
about open ball--

00:41:26.470 --> 00:41:29.760 align:middle line:84%
but I'll try not to
use that term here.

00:41:29.760 --> 00:41:33.060 align:middle line:90%
But open would always mean this.

00:41:33.060 --> 00:41:37.570 align:middle line:84%
Closed ball would mean that
it's less than or equal to.

00:41:37.570 --> 00:41:39.210 align:middle line:90%
Sorry, yeah?

00:41:39.210 --> 00:41:43.370 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Would you talk to me
about the neighborhood example?

00:41:43.370 --> 00:41:46.940 align:middle line:84%
Is that reverse-- is x
in that case a subset?

00:41:46.940 --> 00:41:48.860 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: Yeah,
that's right, exactly.

00:41:48.860 --> 00:41:49.710 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

00:41:49.710 --> 00:41:52.640 align:middle line:90%


00:41:52.640 --> 00:41:57.110 align:middle line:90%
And I didn't actually--

00:41:57.110 --> 00:41:59.400 align:middle line:84%
I already posted
the lecture notes.

00:41:59.400 --> 00:42:01.760 align:middle line:84%
And so in the lecture
notes, I didn't actually

00:42:01.760 --> 00:42:03.360 align:middle line:84%
talk about tubular
neighborhoods.

00:42:03.360 --> 00:42:09.210 align:middle line:84%
But it maybe is
worth thinking about.

00:42:09.210 --> 00:42:13.160 align:middle line:90%
So you could look at it as--

00:42:13.160 --> 00:42:15.205 align:middle line:84%
again, you have a
metric space here.

00:42:15.205 --> 00:42:18.440 align:middle line:90%


00:42:18.440 --> 00:42:21.095 align:middle line:90%
And you could have a subset--

00:42:21.095 --> 00:42:25.850 align:middle line:84%
A has a subset, any subset,
of the metric space.

00:42:25.850 --> 00:42:29.490 align:middle line:84%
And you could define the tubular
neighborhood of a subset.

00:42:29.490 --> 00:42:32.460 align:middle line:84%
And so you could
do this similarly.

00:42:32.460 --> 00:42:37.340 align:middle line:84%
So this would be the y
in x so that the distance

00:42:37.340 --> 00:42:49.980 align:middle line:84%
from y to x here is
strictly less than r

00:42:49.980 --> 00:42:59.830 align:middle line:90%
for some x in a [INAUDIBLE].

00:42:59.830 --> 00:43:02.800 align:middle line:90%
So this is how--

00:43:02.800 --> 00:43:07.020 align:middle line:84%
so again, if you think about
our tree, you take some--

00:43:07.020 --> 00:43:08.940 align:middle line:84%
I mean, maybe we
shouldn't talk about--

00:43:08.940 --> 00:43:13.440 align:middle line:84%
maybe we should draw it more
crazy, like some curve, maybe.

00:43:13.440 --> 00:43:18.040 align:middle line:84%
And if you're looking at the
set that have distance at most--

00:43:18.040 --> 00:43:20.958 align:middle line:84%
this is some sort
of tube, like this.

00:43:20.958 --> 00:43:24.660 align:middle line:90%


00:43:24.660 --> 00:43:27.220 align:middle line:84%
This here would be
the [INAUDIBLE].

00:43:27.220 --> 00:43:30.720 align:middle line:84%
And then here, at the end,
it would look like a cap,

00:43:30.720 --> 00:43:33.150 align:middle line:90%
like this.

00:43:33.150 --> 00:43:35.430 align:middle line:84%
This here would be like
a tubular neighborhood

00:43:35.430 --> 00:43:36.520 align:middle line:90%
of this curve.

00:43:36.520 --> 00:43:39.280 align:middle line:90%


00:43:39.280 --> 00:43:44.950 align:middle line:84%
And so, as you're
saying that in the case

00:43:44.950 --> 00:43:49.730 align:middle line:84%
where A here is just a point,
then those two coincide.

00:43:49.730 --> 00:43:53.060 align:middle line:90%


00:43:53.060 --> 00:43:57.370 align:middle line:84%
So now one of the
key things when

00:43:57.370 --> 00:44:00.760 align:middle line:84%
you're thinking about
convergence in R,

00:44:00.760 --> 00:44:04.810 align:middle line:84%
remember that this stuff, when
we use this time and time again,

00:44:04.810 --> 00:44:06.220 align:middle line:90%
that it was often--

00:44:06.220 --> 00:44:09.940 align:middle line:84%
we saw this for series,
that it was often

00:44:09.940 --> 00:44:15.200 align:middle line:84%
difficult to determine the
exact limit of a series.

00:44:15.200 --> 00:44:19.550 align:middle line:84%
But the question was
always, does it converge?

00:44:19.550 --> 00:44:26.410 align:middle line:84%
And so if it converged, if
it converged, then often, I

00:44:26.410 --> 00:44:29.320 align:middle line:84%
mean, also, if you would
have using this in some

00:44:29.320 --> 00:44:34.210 align:middle line:84%
of application, it's often
in all kind of fields

00:44:34.210 --> 00:44:37.890 align:middle line:84%
that it comes up that things are
written in terms of a series.

00:44:37.890 --> 00:44:41.850 align:middle line:84%
And it's not clear what
it's converting to.

00:44:41.850 --> 00:44:43.920 align:middle line:84%
But you want to know
whether it's converting.

00:44:43.920 --> 00:44:45.990 align:middle line:84%
And then you also
want to-- so you

00:44:45.990 --> 00:44:50.460 align:middle line:84%
want to estimate what is the
limit within a certain error

00:44:50.460 --> 00:44:51.070 align:middle line:90%
term.

00:44:51.070 --> 00:44:53.640 align:middle line:84%
And you can use some of
these comparison tests

00:44:53.640 --> 00:44:59.700 align:middle line:84%
to determine-- to
estimate how close you

00:44:59.700 --> 00:45:01.510 align:middle line:90%
are to the actual limit.

00:45:01.510 --> 00:45:07.260 align:middle line:84%
But in any case, the
thing is it's very useful

00:45:07.260 --> 00:45:11.820 align:middle line:84%
to have a criteria that
is easy to work with

00:45:11.820 --> 00:45:16.170 align:middle line:84%
and that say that it's
converging without having

00:45:16.170 --> 00:45:18.100 align:middle line:90%
to be able to find the limits.

00:45:18.100 --> 00:45:21.610 align:middle line:84%
And like the Cauchy sequence,
this was like a notion of that.

00:45:21.610 --> 00:45:30.450 align:middle line:84%
And so again, the key on
R, the key for using that

00:45:30.450 --> 00:45:34.510 align:middle line:84%
was the Bolzano-Weierstrass
theorem.

00:45:34.510 --> 00:45:39.190 align:middle line:84%
So this was the one that
was the key for using to get

00:45:39.190 --> 00:45:41.690 align:middle line:90%
the quasi convergence theorem.

00:45:41.690 --> 00:45:43.620 align:middle line:84%
So the Bolzano-Weierstrass
theorem--

00:45:43.620 --> 00:45:52.660 align:middle line:90%


00:45:52.660 --> 00:45:58.570 align:middle line:84%
so remember that this
is for any [INAUDIBLE]

00:45:58.570 --> 00:46:11.240 align:middle line:84%
that any bounded sequence
has a convergent subsequence.

00:46:11.240 --> 00:46:22.390 align:middle line:90%


00:46:22.390 --> 00:46:25.270 align:middle line:84%
That was
Bolzano-Weierstrass theorem.

00:46:25.270 --> 00:46:29.440 align:middle line:84%
In a general metric
space, it makes sense

00:46:29.440 --> 00:46:35.510 align:middle line:84%
to talk about a
bounded sequence.

00:46:35.510 --> 00:46:39.020 align:middle line:84%
But it's not always the
case that a bounded sequence

00:46:39.020 --> 00:46:40.830 align:middle line:90%
has a convergent subsequence.

00:46:40.830 --> 00:46:42.570 align:middle line:90%
So it does not hold.

00:46:42.570 --> 00:46:44.070 align:middle line:90%
The Bolzano does not hold.

00:46:44.070 --> 00:46:51.920 align:middle line:84%
So warning,
Bolzano-Weierstrass does not

00:46:51.920 --> 00:46:59.200 align:middle line:90%
hold in a general metric space.

00:46:59.200 --> 00:47:08.600 align:middle line:90%


00:47:08.600 --> 00:47:15.050 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, of course, the
example that we looked at,

00:47:15.050 --> 00:47:18.000 align:middle line:84%
where the example was
x here, like this,

00:47:18.000 --> 00:47:20.010 align:middle line:84%
and when we're looking
at that sequence,

00:47:20.010 --> 00:47:22.820 align:middle line:90%
this is a bounded sequence.

00:47:22.820 --> 00:47:27.150 align:middle line:84%
But it's bounded, but it doesn't
have a convergent subsequence.

00:47:27.150 --> 00:47:28.980 align:middle line:90%
It's actually a Cauchy sequence.

00:47:28.980 --> 00:47:30.110 align:middle line:90%
But it doesn't [INAUDIBLE].

00:47:30.110 --> 00:47:34.360 align:middle line:84%
So it doesn't hold in
a general metric space,

00:47:34.360 --> 00:47:51.960 align:middle line:84%
but it does hold if the
metric space is compact.

00:47:51.960 --> 00:47:54.850 align:middle line:90%


00:47:54.850 --> 00:47:57.320 align:middle line:84%
And so that's what I
want to talk about next.

00:47:57.320 --> 00:48:01.480 align:middle line:84%
But in order to talk about
what it means for metric space

00:48:01.480 --> 00:48:09.610 align:middle line:84%
to be compact, then I
need to talk about--

00:48:09.610 --> 00:48:15.700 align:middle line:84%
I need to define what it
means for a set to be open.

00:48:15.700 --> 00:48:36.500 align:middle line:84%
So we need the notion of
an open set, an open subset

00:48:36.500 --> 00:48:42.340 align:middle line:90%
of a metric space.

00:48:42.340 --> 00:48:49.520 align:middle line:90%


00:48:49.520 --> 00:48:54.530 align:middle line:90%
So we have a metric space again.

00:48:54.530 --> 00:49:00.050 align:middle line:90%
And so A here is said to be--

00:49:00.050 --> 00:49:02.610 align:middle line:90%
let's call it O for open.

00:49:02.610 --> 00:49:21.470 align:middle line:84%
O is said to be an open
subset if for all x in O--

00:49:21.470 --> 00:49:28.440 align:middle line:84%
so the idea is that you
have here, this here is O.

00:49:28.440 --> 00:49:34.410 align:middle line:90%
So this is maybe O.

00:49:34.410 --> 00:49:37.770 align:middle line:84%
And so the idea is
that for each element,

00:49:37.770 --> 00:49:41.920 align:middle line:84%
there exists some ball
centered at that point.

00:49:41.920 --> 00:49:47.090 align:middle line:84%
So for each x for all
x in O, there exists.

00:49:47.090 --> 00:49:52.080 align:middle line:90%


00:49:52.080 --> 00:49:55.410 align:middle line:84%
r greater than 0-- it
may be incredibly small--

00:49:55.410 --> 00:50:02.310 align:middle line:84%
so that not just x but
the whole ball around x

00:50:02.310 --> 00:50:04.180 align:middle line:90%
is contained in the open set.

00:50:04.180 --> 00:50:07.710 align:middle line:84%
So you see that not
just this point here,

00:50:07.710 --> 00:50:12.510 align:middle line:84%
but the whole ball here would
have to be contained in O.

00:50:12.510 --> 00:50:18.040 align:middle line:84%
So in this picture here,
when I'm illustrating this,

00:50:18.040 --> 00:50:22.330 align:middle line:84%
I'm thinking about
x as being R2.

00:50:22.330 --> 00:50:24.210 align:middle line:84%
And I'm thinking
about the distance

00:50:24.210 --> 00:50:25.870 align:middle line:84%
being the usual
Euclidean distance.

00:50:25.870 --> 00:50:28.640 align:middle line:90%


00:50:28.640 --> 00:50:31.080 align:middle line:84%
But then, actually,
if this is open,

00:50:31.080 --> 00:50:35.660 align:middle line:84%
it means that you cannot include
these points here on this curve.

00:50:35.660 --> 00:50:38.220 align:middle line:84%
They would not be
included in the set

00:50:38.220 --> 00:50:42.960 align:middle line:84%
because if you take any point on
this boundary here, so to speak,

00:50:42.960 --> 00:50:48.690 align:middle line:84%
then a ball part of it
would be outside the set.

00:50:48.690 --> 00:50:51.860 align:middle line:84%
So if this really was
open, then this curve

00:50:51.860 --> 00:50:53.550 align:middle line:90%
here was not included.

00:50:53.550 --> 00:50:56.090 align:middle line:84%
And you see that as you're
getting closer and closer

00:50:56.090 --> 00:51:00.800 align:middle line:84%
to that curve, you can still
have a little ball that

00:51:00.800 --> 00:51:02.550 align:middle line:90%
is inside the set.

00:51:02.550 --> 00:51:05.690 align:middle line:84%
But as you're getting closer,
the radius of this little ball

00:51:05.690 --> 00:51:07.610 align:middle line:90%
have to be smaller.

00:51:07.610 --> 00:51:10.160 align:middle line:90%
But that's fine.

00:51:10.160 --> 00:51:15.860 align:middle line:84%
So this is what it means
for a subset to be open.

00:51:15.860 --> 00:51:21.380 align:middle line:84%
And the first thing
that you observe

00:51:21.380 --> 00:51:23.790 align:middle line:90%
that with this definition--

00:51:23.790 --> 00:51:26.680 align:middle line:84%
there are always
two open subsets.

00:51:26.680 --> 00:51:31.410 align:middle line:90%
So again, this thing here--

00:51:31.410 --> 00:51:38.620 align:middle line:90%
so note that the empty set--

00:51:38.620 --> 00:51:39.970 align:middle line:90%
but there's no condition.

00:51:39.970 --> 00:51:43.810 align:middle line:84%
If there was an empty set, say
for all elements in the set,

00:51:43.810 --> 00:51:47.740 align:middle line:84%
But there is no element, so
there's nothing to be satisfied.

00:51:47.740 --> 00:51:53.045 align:middle line:84%
So the empty set and all
of x are open subsets.

00:51:53.045 --> 00:51:59.940 align:middle line:90%


00:51:59.940 --> 00:52:03.160 align:middle line:90%
So do note that.

00:52:03.160 --> 00:52:15.750 align:middle line:84%
So in particular, if so if x
here was not the whole real line

00:52:15.750 --> 00:52:19.410 align:middle line:84%
but it was just the
interval from 0 to 1,

00:52:19.410 --> 00:52:23.170 align:middle line:84%
and then the distance
between elements

00:52:23.170 --> 00:52:26.800 align:middle line:84%
was the usual distance,
then, actually,

00:52:26.800 --> 00:52:32.080 align:middle line:84%
even the closed interval, which
is the whole set, would be open.

00:52:32.080 --> 00:52:37.960 align:middle line:84%
So you just should be careful
with what the set is--

00:52:37.960 --> 00:52:41.740 align:middle line:90%


00:52:41.740 --> 00:52:43.310 align:middle line:90%
what set [INAUDIBLE].

00:52:43.310 --> 00:52:50.140 align:middle line:90%


00:52:50.140 --> 00:52:53.090 align:middle line:90%
So now the key here is that--

00:52:53.090 --> 00:53:01.720 align:middle line:84%
so if you have an open set,
how do you construct a--

00:53:01.720 --> 00:53:04.060 align:middle line:84%
well, maybe the first
thing I should do

00:53:04.060 --> 00:53:11.800 align:middle line:84%
is I should prove a lemma
that is the following.

00:53:11.800 --> 00:53:15.610 align:middle line:84%
And then, after that,
we will talk about how

00:53:15.610 --> 00:53:21.020 align:middle line:90%
to get lots of open sets.

00:53:21.020 --> 00:53:23.650 align:middle line:90%


00:53:23.650 --> 00:53:25.090 align:middle line:90%
So we have two examples.

00:53:25.090 --> 00:53:29.370 align:middle line:84%
At the moment, we
have two examples of--

00:53:29.370 --> 00:53:32.010 align:middle line:84%
so if you take a metric
space, at the moment,

00:53:32.010 --> 00:53:35.250 align:middle line:84%
we know that there's
always two subsets that

00:53:35.250 --> 00:53:38.160 align:middle line:90%
are open, the empty set and x.

00:53:38.160 --> 00:53:40.140 align:middle line:84%
But they're not
very interesting.

00:53:40.140 --> 00:53:45.360 align:middle line:84%
So a more interesting example is
that if you take a metric space

00:53:45.360 --> 00:53:47.050 align:middle line:90%
and you take a ball--

00:53:47.050 --> 00:53:50.410 align:middle line:84%
and now it's crucial
how we define the ball.

00:53:50.410 --> 00:53:56.010 align:middle line:84%
And so it's crucial that
this inequality is strict.

00:53:56.010 --> 00:54:02.520 align:middle line:84%
So for a metric
space x here is in x.

00:54:02.520 --> 00:54:06.730 align:middle line:90%
It could be any element in x.

00:54:06.730 --> 00:54:12.250 align:middle line:84%
This thing here, r here,
is strictly positive.

00:54:12.250 --> 00:54:15.310 align:middle line:84%
It also has to be
strictly positive.

00:54:15.310 --> 00:54:18.430 align:middle line:90%
Then this thing here is open.

00:54:18.430 --> 00:54:25.030 align:middle line:84%
Any metric ball like
this is an open subset.

00:54:25.030 --> 00:54:26.480 align:middle line:90%
Let's try to prove that.

00:54:26.480 --> 00:54:28.300 align:middle line:84%
And again, whether
you're proving things

00:54:28.300 --> 00:54:32.410 align:middle line:84%
like this for a metric space,
the only nontrivial thing

00:54:32.410 --> 00:54:34.250 align:middle line:90%
is the triangle inequality.

00:54:34.250 --> 00:54:37.870 align:middle line:84%
So this is relying on
the triangle inequality.

00:54:37.870 --> 00:54:41.890 align:middle line:84%
And so for a lot of
things, when you're

00:54:41.890 --> 00:54:44.540 align:middle line:84%
proving things about
a metric space,

00:54:44.540 --> 00:54:49.840 align:middle line:84%
it's often quite helpful
to draw a little picture.

00:54:49.840 --> 00:54:54.370 align:middle line:84%
But of course, you have
to be careful with, again,

00:54:54.370 --> 00:54:59.170 align:middle line:84%
then the intuition
comes from Rn.

00:54:59.170 --> 00:55:03.940 align:middle line:84%
And sometimes, the metric is
a little bit more complicated

00:55:03.940 --> 00:55:04.840 align:middle line:90%
than that.

00:55:04.840 --> 00:55:10.730 align:middle line:84%
So this here, imagine that
this is the ball of radius r.

00:55:10.730 --> 00:55:13.480 align:middle line:90%
Here you have some x.

00:55:13.480 --> 00:55:17.000 align:middle line:90%
Now take an element y.

00:55:17.000 --> 00:55:22.700 align:middle line:84%
So suppose that y here
is now in this ball here.

00:55:22.700 --> 00:55:33.860 align:middle line:84%
Then we want to show
that there exists

00:55:33.860 --> 00:55:42.620 align:middle line:84%
that for some s bigger than
0, the ball here of radius

00:55:42.620 --> 00:55:48.530 align:middle line:84%
s around y is now contained
in this ball here.

00:55:48.530 --> 00:55:50.940 align:middle line:90%
So here, you have y.

00:55:50.940 --> 00:55:52.760 align:middle line:84%
And we want to
prove that there is

00:55:52.760 --> 00:55:59.570 align:middle line:84%
some little ball
around y that is

00:55:59.570 --> 00:56:02.270 align:middle line:90%
contained in the original ball.

00:56:02.270 --> 00:56:08.690 align:middle line:84%
And so, again, this is going to
rely on the triangle inequality.

00:56:08.690 --> 00:56:11.760 align:middle line:90%
So you have y here.

00:56:11.760 --> 00:56:14.620 align:middle line:84%
y was supposed to be
in this ball here.

00:56:14.620 --> 00:56:19.780 align:middle line:84%
This means that the
distance from x to y

00:56:19.780 --> 00:56:23.620 align:middle line:90%
is strictly the s in r.

00:56:23.620 --> 00:56:31.600 align:middle line:84%
You take now s here to be
r minus this distance here.

00:56:31.600 --> 00:56:34.000 align:middle line:90%
Why do I do this?

00:56:34.000 --> 00:56:36.910 align:middle line:84%
In my picture here,
I have here x.

00:56:36.910 --> 00:56:39.250 align:middle line:90%
I have here y.

00:56:39.250 --> 00:56:46.840 align:middle line:84%
And our intuition is that if we
go from x and we go through y

00:56:46.840 --> 00:56:49.300 align:middle line:84%
and then we go straight
to the boundary,

00:56:49.300 --> 00:56:55.160 align:middle line:84%
then this thing
here is dx comma y.

00:56:55.160 --> 00:57:01.700 align:middle line:90%
And this one here is r minus d.

00:57:01.700 --> 00:57:04.870 align:middle line:84%
This is the remaining--
this whole here is r.

00:57:04.870 --> 00:57:07.100 align:middle line:90%
This is dx comma y.

00:57:07.100 --> 00:57:10.750 align:middle line:90%
So this here must be this here.

00:57:10.750 --> 00:57:14.330 align:middle line:84%
And so if you're
setting this equal to s,

00:57:14.330 --> 00:57:18.260 align:middle line:84%
and now you imagine taking
a ball here, well, then

00:57:18.260 --> 00:57:20.960 align:middle line:84%
at least on the
picture, this whole ball

00:57:20.960 --> 00:57:23.240 align:middle line:84%
is contained in
the original ball.

00:57:23.240 --> 00:57:27.390 align:middle line:84%
So let's try to
see if that works.

00:57:27.390 --> 00:57:29.900 align:middle line:84%
If that works, then
it really only used

00:57:29.900 --> 00:57:32.180 align:middle line:90%
the triangle inequality.

00:57:32.180 --> 00:57:34.770 align:middle line:84%
So we're setting
s equal to this.

00:57:34.770 --> 00:57:39.900 align:middle line:84%
And then we're looking at
this ball here around S.

00:57:39.900 --> 00:57:44.130 align:middle line:84%
And we take an element
here in this ball.

00:57:44.130 --> 00:57:46.260 align:middle line:90%
And we now need to prove--

00:57:46.260 --> 00:57:47.650 align:middle line:90%
so we need to show.

00:57:47.650 --> 00:57:53.210 align:middle line:90%


00:57:53.210 --> 00:57:55.640 align:middle line:84%
We want to prove that
this whole ball is

00:57:55.640 --> 00:57:57.150 align:middle line:90%
contained in the original ball.

00:57:57.150 --> 00:58:01.160 align:middle line:84%
So this means that we need to
prove that for any such element

00:58:01.160 --> 00:58:06.170 align:middle line:90%
set here is in this thing here.

00:58:06.170 --> 00:58:07.600 align:middle line:90%
That's what we need to prove.

00:58:07.600 --> 00:58:14.220 align:middle line:90%


00:58:14.220 --> 00:58:16.025 align:middle line:90%
And so now you see--

00:58:16.025 --> 00:58:23.590 align:middle line:90%


00:58:23.590 --> 00:58:26.650 align:middle line:90%
so we take z.

00:58:26.650 --> 00:58:29.020 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to
look at this distance.

00:58:29.020 --> 00:58:31.530 align:middle line:84%
In order to prove
this, we need to prove

00:58:31.530 --> 00:58:35.920 align:middle line:84%
that the distance from z to
x is strictly less than r.

00:58:35.920 --> 00:58:38.520 align:middle line:90%
So let's examine that distance.

00:58:38.520 --> 00:58:43.110 align:middle line:84%
Triangle inequality, say, that
this is bounded by the distance

00:58:43.110 --> 00:58:49.890 align:middle line:84%
from x to y plus the
distance from y to z.

00:58:49.890 --> 00:58:58.930 align:middle line:84%
This one here from y to z lie in
the ball of radius s around y.

00:58:58.930 --> 00:59:01.480 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
this thing here,

00:59:01.480 --> 00:59:06.180 align:middle line:84%
this thing here is
strictly less than s.

00:59:06.180 --> 00:59:13.760 align:middle line:84%
And so you see that this thing
here is now less than d x,

00:59:13.760 --> 00:59:19.280 align:middle line:90%
y plus s.

00:59:19.280 --> 00:59:23.895 align:middle line:84%
Now you fill in what
s is, this here.

00:59:23.895 --> 00:59:30.060 align:middle line:90%
s was equal to r minus d x, y.

00:59:30.060 --> 00:59:31.680 align:middle line:90%
That was the definition of s.

00:59:31.680 --> 00:59:34.100 align:middle line:84%
And so now you see
that this thing here

00:59:34.100 --> 00:59:37.830 align:middle line:84%
is r because those
two things cancel out.

00:59:37.830 --> 00:59:40.280 align:middle line:84%
And you see that this
here guarantee you

00:59:40.280 --> 00:59:42.650 align:middle line:90%
that the inequality was strict.

00:59:42.650 --> 00:59:47.150 align:middle line:84%
And so it really
is that whole ball

00:59:47.150 --> 00:59:52.850 align:middle line:84%
was-- so we Conclude that this
whole ball here was contained

00:59:52.850 --> 00:59:55.080 align:middle line:90%
in the original form.

00:59:55.080 --> 01:00:01.130 align:middle line:84%
And again, the proof of it
was just from this picture

01:00:01.130 --> 01:00:04.730 align:middle line:90%
that you make kind of rigorous.

01:00:04.730 --> 01:00:08.190 align:middle line:84%
And the only nontrivial
things at the moment we really

01:00:08.190 --> 01:00:11.563 align:middle line:84%
have in a metric space
is a triangle in concern

01:00:11.563 --> 01:00:13.355 align:middle line:84%
because we haven't
built up a lot of stuff.

01:00:13.355 --> 01:00:17.460 align:middle line:90%


01:00:17.460 --> 01:00:20.580 align:middle line:84%
So you see, this
immediately gives you

01:00:20.580 --> 01:00:29.470 align:middle line:84%
a lot of example of open subsets
of a general metric space.

01:00:29.470 --> 01:00:33.390 align:middle line:84%
And if we had looked at
exactly the same stuff--

01:00:33.390 --> 01:00:36.930 align:middle line:84%
tubular neighborhood-- we would
find that those are also open

01:00:36.930 --> 01:00:37.620 align:middle line:90%
subsets.

01:00:37.620 --> 01:00:38.670 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:00:38.670 --> 01:00:40.570 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Also we
look at subsets,

01:00:40.570 --> 01:00:42.172 align:middle line:90%
or do those have any value?

01:00:42.172 --> 01:00:42.880 align:middle line:90%
PROFESSOR: Close?

01:00:42.880 --> 01:00:45.000 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, very much so.

01:00:45.000 --> 01:00:49.140 align:middle line:84%
But we haven't defined
what it means to be close.

01:00:49.140 --> 01:00:54.870 align:middle line:84%
But you're right,
and we will do this.

01:00:54.870 --> 01:00:59.400 align:middle line:84%
So at the moment, we don't
know what a close thing is.

01:00:59.400 --> 01:01:01.810 align:middle line:90%
And maybe I will just define it.

01:01:01.810 --> 01:01:04.510 align:middle line:90%
And then we can--

01:01:04.510 --> 01:01:08.590 align:middle line:90%


01:01:08.590 --> 01:01:12.010 align:middle line:90%
so let's define.

01:01:12.010 --> 01:01:16.030 align:middle line:84%
But I'll talk more
about this next time--

01:01:16.030 --> 01:01:17.590 align:middle line:90%
but now when you're asking.

01:01:17.590 --> 01:01:20.480 align:middle line:90%


01:01:20.480 --> 01:01:25.630 align:middle line:84%
So we have x here is
a metric space again.

01:01:25.630 --> 01:01:32.483 align:middle line:84%
And then see here, it's a subset
of x is said to be closed.

01:01:32.483 --> 01:01:41.350 align:middle line:90%


01:01:41.350 --> 01:01:44.500 align:middle line:90%
And then now it may--

01:01:44.500 --> 01:01:45.980 align:middle line:90%
seems almost cheating.

01:01:45.980 --> 01:01:49.246 align:middle line:84%
It's said to be closed
if the complement--

01:01:49.246 --> 01:01:54.430 align:middle line:90%


01:01:54.430 --> 01:01:58.375 align:middle line:84%
so this means that
the complement of C--

01:01:58.375 --> 01:02:01.480 align:middle line:90%


01:02:01.480 --> 01:02:17.800 align:middle line:84%
so the complement of C--
these are all the x in x

01:02:17.800 --> 01:02:24.930 align:middle line:90%
so that x is not in C.

01:02:24.930 --> 01:02:28.290 align:middle line:84%
So the complement
a set is everything

01:02:28.290 --> 01:02:31.360 align:middle line:90%
in x that is not in that set.

01:02:31.360 --> 01:02:39.270 align:middle line:84%
And a set is said to be closed
if the complement is open.

01:02:39.270 --> 01:02:43.320 align:middle line:84%
And so now, once you
have this definition

01:02:43.320 --> 01:02:47.340 align:middle line:84%
and now prove this next
time, that if you're

01:02:47.340 --> 01:02:52.110 align:middle line:84%
looking at what I
denote like this,

01:02:52.110 --> 01:03:01.120 align:middle line:84%
so this is the elements
where the distance to x

01:03:01.120 --> 01:03:05.540 align:middle line:84%
is less than or equal to-- so
this is not any more strict.

01:03:05.540 --> 01:03:09.543 align:middle line:84%
This thing here is
then a closed set.

01:03:09.543 --> 01:03:10.960 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Could
you also define it

01:03:10.960 --> 01:03:16.360 align:middle line:84%
by the way we define an open
subset but saying that R instead

01:03:16.360 --> 01:03:17.448 align:middle line:90%
of being strictly?

01:03:17.448 --> 01:03:19.365 align:middle line:84%
PROFESSOR: No, I couldn't
define it like that.

01:03:19.365 --> 01:03:23.110 align:middle line:90%


01:03:23.110 --> 01:03:25.010 align:middle line:84%
So I mean, you could
define it other ways.

01:03:25.010 --> 01:03:27.218 align:middle line:84%
There's another standard
where you would talk about--

01:03:27.218 --> 01:03:30.400 align:middle line:84%
there's another equivalent
to say that if you take--

01:03:30.400 --> 01:03:32.710 align:middle line:84%
but I don't want to
get into that because--

01:03:32.710 --> 01:03:37.690 align:middle line:84%
but there's another
way we get to this.

01:03:37.690 --> 01:03:41.270 align:middle line:84%
And closed sets, we really
mostly talk about next time.

01:03:41.270 --> 01:03:44.230 align:middle line:84%
It was just because
you were asking.

01:03:44.230 --> 01:03:46.550 align:middle line:90%
But let me just talk about--

01:03:46.550 --> 01:03:50.800 align:middle line:84%
so this is one, but I'll just
repeat this in just a second.

01:03:50.800 --> 01:03:56.155 align:middle line:84%
So in order to produce more
sets, so we start with--

01:03:56.155 --> 01:03:59.310 align:middle line:90%


01:03:59.310 --> 01:04:02.180 align:middle line:84%
actually, I should just
note, although just now when

01:04:02.180 --> 01:04:04.740 align:middle line:84%
I talk about, just
the definition,

01:04:04.740 --> 01:04:09.560 align:middle line:84%
I should just immediately note
that there are always two closed

01:04:09.560 --> 01:04:14.780 align:middle line:84%
sets because you see, the
empty set was always open,

01:04:14.780 --> 01:04:17.990 align:middle line:84%
and the full set
was always open.

01:04:17.990 --> 01:04:22.320 align:middle line:84%
And so the complement of the
empty set, that's everything.

01:04:22.320 --> 01:04:24.630 align:middle line:90%
So that's closed.

01:04:24.630 --> 01:04:27.750 align:middle line:84%
And the complement of
everything is nothing.

01:04:27.750 --> 01:04:28.650 align:middle line:90%
It's empty set.

01:04:28.650 --> 01:04:29.910 align:middle line:90%
So that's also closed.

01:04:29.910 --> 01:04:32.390 align:middle line:84%
So those two sets
are always closed.

01:04:32.390 --> 01:04:34.050 align:middle line:90%
But let me just talk about--

01:04:34.050 --> 01:04:40.790 align:middle line:84%
so I want to think about how
do you produce open sets?

01:04:40.790 --> 01:04:46.580 align:middle line:84%
So how do you know that
there are a lot of open sets?

01:04:46.580 --> 01:04:50.460 align:middle line:84%
And so if you take
sets, if you take--

01:04:50.460 --> 01:05:03.735 align:middle line:84%
so this is like operations on
sets on subsets of a given set.

01:05:03.735 --> 01:05:07.570 align:middle line:90%


01:05:07.570 --> 01:05:11.270 align:middle line:84%
So here, I'm thinking about
just x as being a set.

01:05:11.270 --> 01:05:14.530 align:middle line:84%
It does not need to
be a metric space.

01:05:14.530 --> 01:05:21.030 align:middle line:84%
So if I take a set then and I
take two elements, two subsets.

01:05:21.030 --> 01:05:23.680 align:middle line:90%


01:05:23.680 --> 01:05:25.820 align:middle line:90%
So these are two subsets.

01:05:25.820 --> 01:05:30.220 align:middle line:84%
Then I can form the
union of these two.

01:05:30.220 --> 01:05:31.545 align:middle line:90%
This is the union.

01:05:31.545 --> 01:05:36.580 align:middle line:90%


01:05:36.580 --> 01:05:39.380 align:middle line:90%
And the union here of two sets--

01:05:39.380 --> 01:05:41.770 align:middle line:84%
so the union-- and
again, I denote it

01:05:41.770 --> 01:05:45.850 align:middle line:84%
like this,
[INAUDIBLE], like this.

01:05:45.850 --> 01:05:56.990 align:middle line:84%
These are the elements in
x such that x is in u1 or x

01:05:56.990 --> 01:06:01.595 align:middle line:90%
is in u2 or both.

01:06:01.595 --> 01:06:04.700 align:middle line:90%


01:06:04.700 --> 01:06:09.650 align:middle line:84%
And so you often
illustrate this with--

01:06:09.650 --> 01:06:10.790 align:middle line:90%
this is x.

01:06:10.790 --> 01:06:13.010 align:middle line:90%
This is u1.

01:06:13.010 --> 01:06:16.765 align:middle line:90%
This is u2-- u1 and u2.

01:06:16.765 --> 01:06:19.370 align:middle line:90%


01:06:19.370 --> 01:06:25.430 align:middle line:84%
Then this thing
here is the union.

01:06:25.430 --> 01:06:29.360 align:middle line:84%
And likewise, the
intersection is things

01:06:29.360 --> 01:06:32.570 align:middle line:90%
that is lying in both sets.

01:06:32.570 --> 01:06:44.180 align:middle line:84%
So the intersection--
so this is,

01:06:44.180 --> 01:06:46.670 align:middle line:90%
again, you have these two sets.

01:06:46.670 --> 01:06:49.880 align:middle line:90%
And this is the intersection.

01:06:49.880 --> 01:06:55.620 align:middle line:90%
And you denote it like this.

01:06:55.620 --> 01:06:58.080 align:middle line:90%
And this is the x.

01:06:58.080 --> 01:07:02.350 align:middle line:90%
So that x is in u1.

01:07:02.350 --> 01:07:07.650 align:middle line:90%
And x is in u2.

01:07:07.650 --> 01:07:11.220 align:middle line:84%
That's the intersection
of these two sets.

01:07:11.220 --> 01:07:17.290 align:middle line:90%
And then there is a third--

01:07:17.290 --> 01:07:20.560 align:middle line:84%
and then we talk about
generalization of this.

01:07:20.560 --> 01:07:25.000 align:middle line:84%
So there's a third, and
this will complement.

01:07:25.000 --> 01:07:29.070 align:middle line:84%
But let me also
introduce the notation.

01:07:29.070 --> 01:07:38.460 align:middle line:84%
So if you take this subset of x,
then the complement-- and there

01:07:38.460 --> 01:07:47.410 align:middle line:84%
are slightly different ways of
doing it of notation for it.

01:07:47.410 --> 01:07:49.500 align:middle line:84%
And I always use
this one because I

01:07:49.500 --> 01:07:51.490 align:middle line:90%
think that's the clearest one.

01:07:51.490 --> 01:07:55.040 align:middle line:90%
So this is like x take away u.

01:07:55.040 --> 01:07:56.510 align:middle line:90%
And this is totally standard.

01:07:56.510 --> 01:07:58.270 align:middle line:84%
There's another one
that's often used

01:07:58.270 --> 01:08:00.220 align:middle line:84%
where you have C.
That's slightly

01:08:00.220 --> 01:08:01.760 align:middle line:90%
less standard than this one.

01:08:01.760 --> 01:08:03.920 align:middle line:84%
And sometimes, it
can be confusing.

01:08:03.920 --> 01:08:07.060 align:middle line:90%
This one can never be confusing.

01:08:07.060 --> 01:08:09.910 align:middle line:84%
And so this thing
here is a compliment.

01:08:09.910 --> 01:08:14.140 align:middle line:84%
And so this means
that it's the x such

01:08:14.140 --> 01:08:17.069 align:middle line:90%
that x does not belong to u.

01:08:17.069 --> 01:08:24.939 align:middle line:90%


01:08:24.939 --> 01:08:27.529 align:middle line:84%
So that's standard
operation of sets.

01:08:27.529 --> 01:08:31.029 align:middle line:84%
But there is a
generalization of this union

01:08:31.029 --> 01:08:33.910 align:middle line:84%
here, where instead
of just two sets,

01:08:33.910 --> 01:08:36.979 align:middle line:84%
you could take potentially
infinitely many sets.

01:08:36.979 --> 01:08:40.010 align:middle line:84%
So if you take a
family of subsets--

01:08:40.010 --> 01:08:47.460 align:middle line:84%
so alpha here is a
family of subsets.

01:08:47.460 --> 01:08:49.979 align:middle line:90%


01:08:49.979 --> 01:08:54.130 align:middle line:84%
Then you could look at
the union of the u alpha.

01:08:54.130 --> 01:08:56.520 align:middle line:90%
This is denoted like this.

01:08:56.520 --> 01:09:12.120 align:middle line:84%
And this is the x in x such that
x is in u alpha for some alpha.

01:09:12.120 --> 01:09:15.670 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it could be in
many of the u alphas,

01:09:15.670 --> 01:09:18.720 align:middle line:90%
but it has to be at least one.

01:09:18.720 --> 01:09:21.970 align:middle line:84%
So this is the
union of a family.

01:09:21.970 --> 01:09:27.430 align:middle line:84%
And likewise, the intersection
of a family is the x.

01:09:27.430 --> 01:09:31.319 align:middle line:84%
And then it has to now
lie in all of them.

01:09:31.319 --> 01:09:37.790 align:middle line:84%
It's x in x, where x is
in u alpha for all alpha.

01:09:37.790 --> 01:09:42.210 align:middle line:90%


01:09:42.210 --> 01:09:47.500 align:middle line:84%
That's a union and the
intersections of family.

01:09:47.500 --> 01:10:01.750 align:middle line:84%
And so now let me look at
some example in particular.

01:10:01.750 --> 01:10:08.250 align:middle line:84%
Let me look at an
example of this.

01:10:08.250 --> 01:10:16.390 align:middle line:90%


01:10:16.390 --> 01:10:22.870 align:middle line:84%
And then let me prove
something about open sets.

01:10:22.870 --> 01:10:27.100 align:middle line:84%
So let me look at
an example here.

01:10:27.100 --> 01:10:30.730 align:middle line:90%
Suppose that u alpha or u n--

01:10:30.730 --> 01:10:32.830 align:middle line:90%
I'm just going to look at--

01:10:32.830 --> 01:10:38.540 align:middle line:84%
it's going to be now a family
of subsets of the real line.

01:10:38.540 --> 01:10:42.290 align:middle line:84%
And they're going to be
indexed by the natural number.

01:10:42.290 --> 01:10:48.710 align:middle line:84%
So this thing here is going to
be minus 1 over n to 1 over n.

01:10:48.710 --> 01:10:53.360 align:middle line:84%
And if I'm looking at
the union of these guys--

01:10:53.360 --> 01:11:04.380 align:middle line:84%
but you see, this is a
sequence of open sets.

01:11:04.380 --> 01:11:07.530 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it's like for each
n, you have an open set.

01:11:07.530 --> 01:11:11.010 align:middle line:84%
But as n gets larger,
they're smaller.

01:11:11.010 --> 01:11:12.810 align:middle line:84%
The first one is
the biggest one.

01:11:12.810 --> 01:11:16.010 align:middle line:84%
So if you take the
union of these guys,

01:11:16.010 --> 01:11:20.070 align:middle line:84%
that just gives you the
first one you started with.

01:11:20.070 --> 01:11:23.600 align:middle line:90%
So this is the union of these.

01:11:23.600 --> 01:11:26.960 align:middle line:84%
If you take the
intersection of them,

01:11:26.960 --> 01:11:31.820 align:middle line:84%
well, the only thing that is
in all of these sets, that's

01:11:31.820 --> 01:11:32.845 align:middle line:90%
actually the 0.

01:11:32.845 --> 01:11:39.410 align:middle line:90%


01:11:39.410 --> 01:11:48.750 align:middle line:84%
Now we need some stuff
about operations of sets.

01:11:48.750 --> 01:11:52.790 align:middle line:90%


01:11:52.790 --> 01:11:56.890 align:middle line:84%
And so there's some
standard operations.

01:11:56.890 --> 01:12:07.000 align:middle line:84%
And my recommendation is that
not try to remember this.

01:12:07.000 --> 01:12:08.480 align:middle line:90%
I don't remember it myself.

01:12:08.480 --> 01:12:10.400 align:middle line:90%
So I always have to run through.

01:12:10.400 --> 01:12:14.270 align:middle line:84%
But once you have
done it once or twice,

01:12:14.270 --> 01:12:18.710 align:middle line:84%
the proof is so trivial that
it's not worth remembering.

01:12:18.710 --> 01:12:22.820 align:middle line:84%
And I think the danger if you
try to remember these things,

01:12:22.820 --> 01:12:24.620 align:middle line:90%
you may remember it wrong.

01:12:24.620 --> 01:12:27.820 align:middle line:84%
And that's much worse than
just running through the proof.

01:12:27.820 --> 01:12:33.880 align:middle line:84%
So you have the
following lemma here.

01:12:33.880 --> 01:12:37.347 align:middle line:84%
So you have a set, and
then you have subsets.

01:12:37.347 --> 01:12:40.060 align:middle line:90%


01:12:40.060 --> 01:12:48.620 align:middle line:84%
Let's call it A, B, and
then a family of subsets.

01:12:48.620 --> 01:12:51.560 align:middle line:84%
And the thing is
the first one is

01:12:51.560 --> 01:12:56.630 align:middle line:84%
that if you take the
complement of the complement,

01:12:56.630 --> 01:13:01.220 align:middle line:84%
so if you take A and you take
everything that is not in A--

01:13:01.220 --> 01:13:03.800 align:middle line:90%


01:13:03.800 --> 01:13:07.530 align:middle line:84%
so just think about it that if
you take-- so here you have x.

01:13:07.530 --> 01:13:11.120 align:middle line:84%
Here, you have A. This
is A. Everything that

01:13:11.120 --> 01:13:14.790 align:middle line:90%
is not in A, that's over here.

01:13:14.790 --> 01:13:18.420 align:middle line:84%
But then if it's not
over here, then it's A.

01:13:18.420 --> 01:13:22.500 align:middle line:90%
So the first one is just that.

01:13:22.500 --> 01:13:25.650 align:middle line:84%
And actually, just because
we're also running out of time,

01:13:25.650 --> 01:13:27.180 align:middle line:90%
we really proved this.

01:13:27.180 --> 01:13:31.010 align:middle line:84%
I mean, so if you have
something that is not in A,

01:13:31.010 --> 01:13:32.930 align:middle line:90%
then it's like here.

01:13:32.930 --> 01:13:36.030 align:middle line:84%
But if it's not like here
then it's like A there.

01:13:36.030 --> 01:13:38.510 align:middle line:90%
That's that statement.

01:13:38.510 --> 01:13:47.500 align:middle line:84%
The second one is that if you
take the complement of that,

01:13:47.500 --> 01:13:51.320 align:middle line:90%
it's in the union of these guys.

01:13:51.320 --> 01:13:55.830 align:middle line:90%


01:13:55.830 --> 01:14:01.020 align:middle line:84%
So if it's not, this
just means that it's not

01:14:01.020 --> 01:14:03.160 align:middle line:90%
in any of these guys.

01:14:03.160 --> 01:14:05.890 align:middle line:90%
This here is the set.

01:14:05.890 --> 01:14:09.780 align:middle line:84%
Imagine that you have
something that looks like--

01:14:09.780 --> 01:14:12.930 align:middle line:84%
you have a bunch
of sets like this.

01:14:12.930 --> 01:14:18.310 align:middle line:84%
This is supposed to
illustrate the A alphas.

01:14:18.310 --> 01:14:21.420 align:middle line:84%
And if it's not this,
just say that if it's not

01:14:21.420 --> 01:14:29.220 align:middle line:84%
in any of these, well, then
the claim is that, then, it's

01:14:29.220 --> 01:14:31.470 align:middle line:90%
in the intersection of--

01:14:31.470 --> 01:14:35.640 align:middle line:84%
that it's not in this
one, it's not in this one,

01:14:35.640 --> 01:14:38.650 align:middle line:84%
and it's not in this one,
and it's not in that one.

01:14:38.650 --> 01:14:40.350 align:middle line:90%
So that's also clear enough.

01:14:40.350 --> 01:14:46.280 align:middle line:90%
So this is the second one.

01:14:46.280 --> 01:14:52.820 align:middle line:84%
Again, I actually wrote
out the proof in the notes.

01:14:52.820 --> 01:14:54.715 align:middle line:90%
So you can check that out.

01:14:54.715 --> 01:15:03.500 align:middle line:90%


01:15:03.500 --> 01:15:16.010 align:middle line:84%
And the third operation
is that if you take x,

01:15:16.010 --> 01:15:22.060 align:middle line:84%
and you are removing the
intersection of this family--

01:15:22.060 --> 01:15:24.800 align:middle line:90%


01:15:24.800 --> 01:15:27.990 align:middle line:90%
so this means that it is not--

01:15:27.990 --> 01:15:30.470 align:middle line:84%
so this means that
the intersection

01:15:30.470 --> 01:15:35.490 align:middle line:84%
of the family in this picture
here would be this thing here.

01:15:35.490 --> 01:15:38.710 align:middle line:90%
And so it's not right there.

01:15:38.710 --> 01:15:41.010 align:middle line:90%
Everything else is allowed.

01:15:41.010 --> 01:15:42.520 align:middle line:90%
But that's the same.

01:15:42.520 --> 01:15:47.990 align:middle line:84%
You see, that's the same
as the union of x take away

01:15:47.990 --> 01:15:58.680 align:middle line:84%
A. This here is the element
that is not in one of-- there's

01:15:58.680 --> 01:16:01.620 align:middle line:84%
at least one of the
u alpha, A alpha,

01:16:01.620 --> 01:16:05.730 align:middle line:84%
where it's not in, and
so that's the same.

01:16:05.730 --> 01:16:09.780 align:middle line:90%
So this is the same as this.

01:16:09.780 --> 01:16:14.470 align:middle line:84%
Again, I wrote it
out in the notes--

01:16:14.470 --> 01:16:16.690 align:middle line:84%
the proof, actually,
of these things.

01:16:16.690 --> 01:16:20.940 align:middle line:90%


01:16:20.940 --> 01:16:23.190 align:middle line:90%
And let me just say--

01:16:23.190 --> 01:16:27.480 align:middle line:84%
maybe we can't quite I mean,
we'll pick up in the notes

01:16:27.480 --> 01:16:30.790 align:middle line:90%
where the other stuff--

01:16:30.790 --> 01:16:36.410 align:middle line:84%
but let me just say that
when you prove of thing,

01:16:36.410 --> 01:16:43.600 align:middle line:84%
and we even did this here
when I'm just illustrating it

01:16:43.600 --> 01:16:45.040 align:middle line:90%
with a picture.

01:16:45.040 --> 01:16:51.650 align:middle line:84%
So we prove it using the
following trivial lemma.

01:16:51.650 --> 01:16:54.610 align:middle line:84%
And I wrote that out as
a lemma in the notes,

01:16:54.610 --> 01:16:59.180 align:middle line:84%
that if you are trying to
prove that two sets are equal--

01:16:59.180 --> 01:17:02.500 align:middle line:84%
so suppose you're trying to
prove that two sets are equal.

01:17:02.500 --> 01:17:07.070 align:middle line:84%
Then, in a way, it's natural
to divide this into two parts.

01:17:07.070 --> 01:17:23.950 align:middle line:84%
So this is the same as proving
that A is contained in B and B

01:17:23.950 --> 01:17:27.760 align:middle line:84%
is contained in A.
So if you're trying

01:17:27.760 --> 01:17:29.810 align:middle line:84%
to prove that two
sets are equal,

01:17:29.810 --> 01:17:34.860 align:middle line:84%
then you would prove that for
any elements in A, it's also B,

01:17:34.860 --> 01:17:36.120 align:middle line:90%
this is this thing.

01:17:36.120 --> 01:17:39.940 align:middle line:84%
And you prove that for any
element B, it's also in A.

01:17:39.940 --> 01:17:46.690 align:middle line:84%
And so when I wrote out the
proof of these three things,

01:17:46.690 --> 01:17:51.030 align:middle line:84%
then I wrote it out like each
of them has two parts that you

01:17:51.030 --> 01:17:53.385 align:middle line:84%
prove that this set
is contained in that

01:17:53.385 --> 01:17:55.260 align:middle line:84%
and you prove that this
is contained in that.

01:17:55.260 --> 01:17:59.580 align:middle line:90%


01:17:59.580 --> 01:18:05.370 align:middle line:90%
Now we're almost actually there.

01:18:05.370 --> 01:18:15.630 align:middle line:84%
So now let me just say
that-- so that's actually

01:18:15.630 --> 01:18:21.430 align:middle line:90%
in one of the Pset problems.

01:18:21.430 --> 01:18:24.450 align:middle line:90%
But there's no Pset.

01:18:24.450 --> 01:18:27.480 align:middle line:84%
You have a little
break now for Psets

01:18:27.480 --> 01:18:31.020 align:middle line:84%
because I want to make sure that
there is no Pset material we

01:18:31.020 --> 01:18:34.330 align:middle line:84%
haven't yet covered in class,
so that's why there's a break.

01:18:34.330 --> 01:18:39.020 align:middle line:84%
And anyway, all of the Psets at
this point are actually posted.

01:18:39.020 --> 01:18:41.330 align:middle line:90%
So the last one I think is due--

01:18:41.330 --> 01:18:44.330 align:middle line:84%
I forget whether it's the 8
of May or something like that.

01:18:44.330 --> 01:18:46.790 align:middle line:90%
And again, there's five left.

01:18:46.790 --> 01:18:48.940 align:middle line:90%
You've already done [INAUDIBLE].

01:18:48.940 --> 01:18:57.650 align:middle line:84%
So now if x here, d
is a metric space,

01:18:57.650 --> 01:19:00.490 align:middle line:84%
then you have the
following lemma

01:19:00.490 --> 01:19:09.670 align:middle line:84%
that if O alpha
are open subsets,

01:19:09.670 --> 01:19:13.890 align:middle line:84%
then the union of
the O alpha is also--

01:19:13.890 --> 01:19:20.200 align:middle line:90%


01:19:20.200 --> 01:19:22.340 align:middle line:84%
But this is quite
trivial, as you see.

01:19:22.340 --> 01:19:23.810 align:middle line:90%
I'll just indicate why.

01:19:23.810 --> 01:19:26.150 align:middle line:84%
But it's actually
left on a Pset.

01:19:26.150 --> 01:19:27.320 align:middle line:90%
So the proof here--

01:19:27.320 --> 01:19:30.320 align:middle line:90%


01:19:30.320 --> 01:19:32.600 align:middle line:84%
but I will just
illustrate it anyway

01:19:32.600 --> 01:19:40.340 align:middle line:84%
that if you take an element
here in the union, well,

01:19:40.340 --> 01:19:44.540 align:middle line:84%
this means that there
exists a value added.

01:19:44.540 --> 01:19:50.120 align:middle line:84%
So it means that x is in
O alpha for some alpha.

01:19:50.120 --> 01:19:56.030 align:middle line:90%


01:19:56.030 --> 01:19:59.480 align:middle line:84%
But this means that
there is a ball around it

01:19:59.480 --> 01:20:01.140 align:middle line:90%
because this here is open.

01:20:01.140 --> 01:20:03.890 align:middle line:84%
It means that there's
a little ball around it

01:20:03.890 --> 01:20:08.480 align:middle line:90%
that is contained in this.

01:20:08.480 --> 01:20:11.390 align:middle line:84%
But therefore,
it's also contained

01:20:11.390 --> 01:20:17.270 align:middle line:90%
in the union of these guys.

01:20:17.270 --> 01:20:20.270 align:middle line:84%
And so this is
really just a proof

01:20:20.270 --> 01:20:24.580 align:middle line:84%
that the union of
open sets are open.

01:20:24.580 --> 01:20:27.138 align:middle line:90%


01:20:27.138 --> 01:20:28.930 align:middle line:84%
We're out of time now,
but next time, we'll

01:20:28.930 --> 01:20:32.170 align:middle line:84%
talk about why if you
take finitely many

01:20:32.170 --> 01:20:39.170 align:middle line:84%
sets, why the intersection
of finitely many open sets,

01:20:39.170 --> 01:20:40.960 align:middle line:90%
why that is also open.

01:20:40.960 --> 01:20:44.420 align:middle line:84%
But for intersection
of open sets,

01:20:44.420 --> 01:20:48.760 align:middle line:84%
you have to be careful
because for union, you

01:20:48.760 --> 01:20:51.860 align:middle line:84%
can take the union of
any number of open sets.

01:20:51.860 --> 01:20:53.000 align:middle line:90%
It's always open.

01:20:53.000 --> 01:20:58.280 align:middle line:84%
But if you take
intersection u, in general,

01:20:58.280 --> 01:21:02.300 align:middle line:84%
it's only true that finite
intersections are open.

01:21:02.300 --> 01:21:04.390 align:middle line:84%
And the example is
one of the examples

01:21:04.390 --> 01:21:09.950 align:middle line:84%
we looked at before where
you take these sets here.

01:21:09.950 --> 01:21:13.030 align:middle line:90%
These sets are open subsets.

01:21:13.030 --> 01:21:16.130 align:middle line:84%
But if you take the
intersection of all of them,

01:21:16.130 --> 01:21:17.980 align:middle line:90%
then you just get 0.

01:21:17.980 --> 01:21:20.530 align:middle line:90%
And that's not an open subset.

01:21:20.530 --> 01:21:24.720 align:middle line:90%
So we're done.

01:21:24.720 --> 01:21:27.000 align:middle line:90%